WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.240
[Amit Varma]: There is a story I have told a couple of times on this show, and while it's a true story,

00:00:09.240 --> 00:00:14.080
[Amit Varma]: it's not the full story. There is another side to it. Let me tell you that story again.

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:17.720
[Amit Varma]: A few years ago, I was hanging with a friend who worked closely with Narendra Modi in the

00:00:17.720 --> 00:00:22.040
[Amit Varma]: auties. She has fallen out with him since, but for a period of time when Modi was the

00:00:22.040 --> 00:00:26.520
[Amit Varma]: Chief Minister, she was his friend. And she told me that one day, in his residence, some

00:00:26.520 --> 00:00:30.720
[Amit Varma]: of them were hanging with him, maybe six or seven people, and Modi told them a story.

00:00:30.720 --> 00:00:35.100
[Amit Varma]: He said that one day when he was a kid, his mother fell ill. At one point, she felt hot

00:00:35.100 --> 00:00:39.960
[Amit Varma]: and wanted the fan on. The young Narendra went to switch on the fan, and then realized

00:00:39.960 --> 00:00:43.880
[Amit Varma]: that there was no electricity. And he couldn't even do this for his mother. When he reached

00:00:43.880 --> 00:00:48.800
[Amit Varma]: this point of the story, Modi started crying. My friend's point was that this is how he

00:00:48.800 --> 00:00:53.640
[Amit Varma]: understands the world, through experience. He's an experiential Prime Minister, or as

00:00:53.640 --> 00:00:58.360
[Amit Varma]: I wrote in a column later, an aankho dekhi Prime Minister. He has experienced the importance

00:00:58.360 --> 00:01:03.440
[Amit Varma]: of electricity, so when he becomes CM of Gujarat, he makes it his mission to electrify as many

00:01:03.440 --> 00:01:08.440
[Amit Varma]: villages as he can. Similarly, he has walked on roads, and he can see their importance,

00:01:08.440 --> 00:01:13.200
[Amit Varma]: and so on. And my friend who told me this story felt, and I agreed, that this approach

00:01:13.200 --> 00:01:17.520
[Amit Varma]: has its limitations. There are some things you can experience and understand, and there

00:01:17.520 --> 00:01:22.240
[Amit Varma]: are others that you can't. They may be outside your experience, or they may be frameworks,

00:01:22.240 --> 00:01:27.840
[Amit Varma]: ways of looking at the world, which affect real people and remain unseen. Like spontaneous

00:01:27.840 --> 00:01:32.280
[Amit Varma]: order, for example, or the power of voluntary exchange, or the countless oppressions of

00:01:32.280 --> 00:01:37.720
[Amit Varma]: the state that we have normalized. This is why Modi as Prime Minister made huge blunders

00:01:37.720 --> 00:01:42.000
[Amit Varma]: like demonetization. There was no way he could have understood the working of the economy

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:46.360
[Amit Varma]: from direct experience. And he had never learned the mental frameworks that would help him

00:01:46.360 --> 00:01:49.560
[Amit Varma]: make sense of this. Now in the column I wrote about this, which I'll link from the show

00:01:49.560 --> 00:01:54.560
[Amit Varma]: notes, I made this an argument for reading. How can we learn those things about the world

00:01:54.560 --> 00:01:59.160
[Amit Varma]: which direct experience may not teach us? We do it through reading. The lives of others,

00:01:59.160 --> 00:02:04.080
[Amit Varma]: the thoughts of others, all of human knowledge is available to us. And while one can't blame

00:02:04.080 --> 00:02:08.520
[Amit Varma]: Modi for not being much of a reader, as he didn't have that sort of privileged upbringing,

00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:13.400
[Amit Varma]: he should have realized his limitation, remained humble about the extent of his knowledge,

00:02:13.400 --> 00:02:18.920
[Amit Varma]: and read more, listened to experts more, instead of pushing them away. Now this story, this

00:02:18.920 --> 00:02:22.880
[Amit Varma]: narrative, while it is the truth, is not the whole truth. There is an opposite problem

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:27.040
[Amit Varma]: also. That opposite problem is this. You may have all the intellectual knowledge in the

00:02:27.040 --> 00:02:31.640
[Amit Varma]: world, theories about public policy, notions of how to make the world better, and you may

00:02:31.640 --> 00:02:36.000
[Amit Varma]: imprison yourself in an ivory tower because you feel you know it all, and you don't need

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.720
[Amit Varma]: to interact with reality because hey, you get it. This is also a mistake, and it leads

00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:44.840
[Amit Varma]: to a top-down way of thinking. In fact, if you consider Jawaharlal Nehru and Narendra

00:02:44.840 --> 00:02:50.000
[Amit Varma]: Modi, they both came to the fatal conceit of top-down central planning, but they came

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:54.800
[Amit Varma]: to it from different roads. Nehru's intellectual arrogance, and I had a recent episode on this

00:02:54.800 --> 00:02:58.080
[Amit Varma]: I urge you to listen to with Rupert Dhaman Singh and Adil Hussain, which I linked from

00:02:58.080 --> 00:03:02.680
[Amit Varma]: the show notes, Nehru's intellectual arrogance led him to believe that he had figured out

00:03:02.680 --> 00:03:08.200
[Amit Varma]: deep truths about the economy and society, and he could engineer both from the top-down.

00:03:08.200 --> 00:03:12.800
[Amit Varma]: He was wrong, and he failed. Modi thinks that what he has learned from his experience of

00:03:12.800 --> 00:03:17.280
[Amit Varma]: the world is all that needs to be learned, and now he must guide others from the top-down,

00:03:17.280 --> 00:03:22.920
[Amit Varma]: like a wise sage. He is also wrong, and he has also failed. And the big lesson in this

00:03:22.920 --> 00:03:27.840
[Amit Varma]: is something that my guest today figured out through years of being both an intellectual

00:03:27.840 --> 00:03:32.640
[Amit Varma]: and a grassroots activist, that a true understanding of the world can only come in a bottom-up

00:03:32.640 --> 00:03:38.160
[Amit Varma]: way. The world is complex, there is always more to it than you think you understand.

00:03:38.160 --> 00:03:59.080
[Amit Varma]: We cannot stop searching for the truth, and the truth lies out there, not in here.

00:03:59.080 --> 00:04:03.400
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen. My guest today is a man I adore, a dear friend, a wise

00:04:03.400 --> 00:04:08.560
[Amit Varma]: guide, a man I call Dadamoni. Barun Mitra is that rare creature who is both a man of

00:04:08.560 --> 00:04:13.160
[Amit Varma]: ideas and a man of action. He was a prolific participant in the marketplace of ideas from

00:04:13.160 --> 00:04:19.240
[Amit Varma]: the 1990s, writing powerful, counter-intuitive and thought-provoking pieces. He also founded

00:04:19.240 --> 00:04:24.420
[Amit Varma]: a classical liberal think-tank, or a libertarian think-tank, called the Liberty Institute.

00:04:24.420 --> 00:04:30.160
[Amit Varma]: He was also always a grassroots worker. He threw himself into various farmer's movements,

00:04:30.160 --> 00:04:35.000
[Amit Varma]: supporting a mass agitation led by the great Sharad Joshi that led to actual policy change

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:39.600
[Amit Varma]: around two decades ago. He also participated in a remarkable movement to get property rights

00:04:39.600 --> 00:04:44.360
[Amit Varma]: for tribals, in which modern technology played a part in solving an ancient problem. We'll

00:04:44.360 --> 00:04:48.640
[Amit Varma]: discuss both of these in our conversation, the highlight of which is when he shares how

00:04:48.640 --> 00:04:53.900
[Amit Varma]: in his journey, he realised that for his ideas to mean anything, they have to be informed

00:04:53.900 --> 00:04:59.440
[Amit Varma]: by ground realities. His idol, and someone we discuss here, is Mahatma Gandhi, who made

00:04:59.440 --> 00:05:04.760
[Amit Varma]: our freedom movement into a mass movement, by taking his ideas to the people, by putting

00:05:04.760 --> 00:05:09.320
[Amit Varma]: them first. Barun says, a key moment in his way of thinking about the world, was when

00:05:09.320 --> 00:05:15.660
[Amit Varma]: he realised that the important word in the phrase public policy, is not policy, but public.

00:05:15.660 --> 00:05:20.280
[Amit Varma]: You have to go past the abstract and look at the concrete. I have always admired Barun

00:05:20.280 --> 00:05:24.200
[Amit Varma]: for his clarity and depth of engagement, and when I double clicked on those, I realised

00:05:24.200 --> 00:05:29.360
[Amit Varma]: where they came from. His clarity comes from his curiosity. He always tests his ideas and

00:05:29.360 --> 00:05:35.120
[Amit Varma]: he's open to challenge. His engagement comes from his genuine empathy. Over the years I've

00:05:35.120 --> 00:05:39.040
[Amit Varma]: learnt a lot from Barun, and I could go on and on talking about this, but why don't you

00:05:39.040 --> 00:05:42.840
[Amit Varma]: listen to this conversation instead, which by the way, we had in November, that's when

00:05:42.840 --> 00:05:49.560
[Amit Varma]: I recorded this. Do listen, but before that, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:05:49.560 --> 00:05:53.120
[Amit Varma]: Have you always wanted to be a writer, but never quite gotten down to it? Well, I'd love

00:05:53.120 --> 00:05:57.800
[Amit Varma]: to help you. Since April 2020, I've taught 20 cohorts of my online course, The Art of

00:05:57.800 --> 00:06:02.240
[Amit Varma]: Clear Writing. An online community has now sprung up of all my past students. We have

00:06:02.240 --> 00:06:07.200
[Amit Varma]: workshops, a newsletter to showcase the work of students, and vibrant community interaction.

00:06:07.200 --> 00:06:11.520
[Amit Varma]: In the course itself, through four webinars spread over four weekends, I share all I know

00:06:11.520 --> 00:06:15.720
[Amit Varma]: about the craft and practice of clear writing. There are many exercises, much interaction,

00:06:15.720 --> 00:06:20.160
[Amit Varma]: a lovely and lively community at the end of it. The course costs Rs. 10,000 plus GST,

00:06:20.160 --> 00:06:24.960
[Amit Varma]: or about $150, and is a monthly thing. So if you're interested, head on over to register

00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:30.440
[Amit Varma]: at indiauncut.com slash clear writing. That's indiauncut.com slash clear writing. Being

00:06:30.440 --> 00:06:35.720
[Amit Varma]: a good writer doesn't require God given talent, just the willingness to work hard and a clear

00:06:35.720 --> 00:06:40.240
[Amit Varma]: idea of what you need to do to refine your skills. I can help you.

00:06:40.240 --> 00:06:42.520
[Amit Varma]: Barun, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:06:42.520 --> 00:06:46.440
[Guest]: Thanks, Amit. I'm still wondering why am I here, but thanks for having me.

00:06:46.440 --> 00:06:51.080
[Amit Varma]: Firstly, you've been here before. Secondly, this is an episode I'm excited about because

00:06:51.080 --> 00:06:54.800
[Amit Varma]: I'll just tell my listeners that when Barun just sat down, he was like, why are you calling

00:06:54.800 --> 00:06:58.000
[Amit Varma]: me? I have no accomplishments. I haven't written books. And it's true, he hasn't written books,

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:02.360
[Amit Varma]: so he should. But my whole point was that one, accomplishments are something which is

00:07:02.360 --> 00:07:07.840
[Amit Varma]: not up to us to judge. Barun, your social work is so immense that, you know, some of

00:07:07.840 --> 00:07:12.760
[Amit Varma]: the value of it is perhaps incalculable. And also, you know, one of my friends once described

00:07:12.760 --> 00:07:17.920
[Amit Varma]: himself as a person who collects interesting people. And I think in a manner of speaking

00:07:17.920 --> 00:07:23.480
[Amit Varma]: through the show, I have conversations which make me think and therefore by extension also

00:07:23.480 --> 00:07:28.760
[Amit Varma]: make listeners hopefully think. And the other thing that I have realized is that when I

00:07:28.760 --> 00:07:33.400
[Amit Varma]: speak with people I already know as friends, like we've known each other for 15-20 years,

00:07:33.400 --> 00:07:37.760
[Amit Varma]: like you just mentioned, I find that after the conversation, I realized I hadn't known

00:07:37.760 --> 00:07:42.800
[Amit Varma]: them at all, because we talk about so much else. So that's kind of what we do. Like,

00:07:42.800 --> 00:07:46.520
[Amit Varma]: since I have known you, you have basically been father time with your flowing white beard

00:07:46.520 --> 00:07:51.840
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. A 21st century libertarian Marx, as it were. So tell me a little bit

00:07:51.840 --> 00:07:55.960
[Amit Varma]: about sort of your childhood, where were you born? Where did you grow up? What were your

00:07:55.960 --> 00:08:01.560
[Amit Varma]: early years like? Give me a sense of the texture of your life, because the texture of these

00:08:01.560 --> 00:08:07.080
[Amit Varma]: modern times are so different, where we are surrounded by smartphones and sensory influences

00:08:07.080 --> 00:08:11.440
[Amit Varma]: and networks and all of that, but it wasn't like that when you were growing up.

00:08:11.440 --> 00:08:19.960
[Guest]: Yeah, it wasn't like that. And, you know, I'm kind of split on history or the past,

00:08:19.960 --> 00:08:29.920
[Guest]: mine or otherwise, because, you know, we seem to invariably draw kind of very destructive

00:08:29.920 --> 00:08:38.900
[Guest]: lessons from history. I rarely look back as such, except to figure out how is it going

00:08:38.900 --> 00:08:46.800
[Guest]: to shape or influence what I'm going to do next. So I rarely, I mean, I rarely look back

00:08:46.800 --> 00:08:55.680
[Guest]: in any particular meaningful sense. But, and I grew up in a, you know, compared to you,

00:08:55.680 --> 00:09:04.480
[Guest]: I grew up probably 10-20 years before you. I think you've just passed 60 and I'm 47.

00:09:04.480 --> 00:09:10.960
[Guest]: I'm probably heading towards 61. Why probably? You might be father time, but you haven't

00:09:10.960 --> 00:09:24.080
[Guest]: stopped time. I was born in Calcutta and a very different Calcutta, a city that's still

00:09:24.080 --> 00:09:31.280
[Guest]: my home. And that actually also shows every time I go back to Alcatraz, it kind of a benchmark

00:09:31.280 --> 00:09:40.680
[Guest]: for me to where we are and where we were. I mean, personally, socially, city, collectively,

00:09:40.680 --> 00:09:48.120
[Guest]: community wise. Yeah, it's a sea change. And I studied in a Bengali school. So that was

00:09:48.120 --> 00:09:56.560
[Guest]: one of my first kind of throwback. My primary education was in a Bengali medium, you know,

00:09:56.560 --> 00:10:05.680
[Guest]: like a local school, like most of us in those days. And then the Naxalite movement happened

00:10:05.680 --> 00:10:15.760
[Guest]: in the late 60s. And my father had been in politics since his youth days. He was a member

00:10:15.760 --> 00:10:23.880
[Guest]: of the Congress and a manager of the local, election manager for the local MLA, MP. So

00:10:23.880 --> 00:10:30.280
[Guest]: it was a challenging time for him and for us and the schools, etc, were to shut. So

00:10:30.280 --> 00:10:38.560
[Guest]: my father shifted me to my uncle, who was then in Madhya Pradesh. And so my first shock

00:10:38.560 --> 00:10:47.120
[Guest]: was for all of them and me was, I had no knowledge of English, nor Hindi. You know, English,

00:10:47.120 --> 00:10:51.760
[Guest]: I could read alphabets, but nothing more than that. And Hindi, I had no knowledge. And you

00:10:51.760 --> 00:11:01.280
[Guest]: were like 9 or 10. Yeah, probably. And so that was a shock and what kind of amazed me

00:11:01.280 --> 00:11:08.080
[Guest]: and what I still remember, I don't remember the name of the class teacher. But I do remember

00:11:08.080 --> 00:11:17.880
[Guest]: the length to which she went to have me in the class and yet prepare me in a way for

00:11:17.880 --> 00:11:25.240
[Guest]: which I needed to be prepared because I was far behind the class in virtually every subject.

00:11:25.240 --> 00:11:31.200
[Guest]: And that to me was quite an interesting because I was different, yet I was made to feel, you

00:11:31.200 --> 00:11:37.640
[Guest]: know, part of the same class. So that was, I mean, looking back was one of my nice pleasant

00:11:37.640 --> 00:11:46.500
[Guest]: experience that she took so much trouble and that's how, I mean, English became my second

00:11:46.500 --> 00:11:55.440
[Guest]: language as such. Otherwise, I probably wouldn't have. But then I came back to Calcutta for

00:11:55.440 --> 00:12:02.760
[Guest]: my higher secondary and did my engineering. You know, in my days, from my kind of a family,

00:12:02.760 --> 00:12:08.240
[Guest]: you either had to be a doctor or an engineer. Yeah, I mean, there was literally no option

00:12:08.240 --> 00:12:13.000
[Guest]: and we just tried our luck that whichever we got and I got engineering. So I went for

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:21.520
[Guest]: engineering in the REC Suratkal. So that was another first, for instance, for my class

00:12:21.520 --> 00:12:27.880
[Guest]: or my friends, I was probably the first one who was put on a flight and asked to go to

00:12:27.880 --> 00:12:36.160
[Guest]: the college on his own and figure out everything of admission, which compared to what's happening

00:12:36.160 --> 00:12:43.120
[Guest]: today and I see all around me is, you know, people don't believe. It was fun and the best

00:12:43.120 --> 00:12:48.640
[Guest]: part was that that college five years that I spent my engineering was five years, those

00:12:48.640 --> 00:12:58.080
[Guest]: days it was 11 plus 5. And I really enjoyed it. One because the experience itself outside

00:12:58.080 --> 00:13:04.440
[Guest]: the outside home and alone and in a very cosmopolitan place because regional engineering colleges

00:13:04.440 --> 00:13:10.400
[Guest]: were literally mini India. Yeah, I had no idea of South India when I landed there. So

00:13:10.400 --> 00:13:16.160
[Guest]: to get used to everything, the food and people, the language and everything. But most importantly,

00:13:16.160 --> 00:13:21.560
[Guest]: what I remember and what I really, you know, what's this my kind of second bright spot

00:13:21.560 --> 00:13:25.160
[Guest]: was that that college was located on the beach, literally.

00:13:25.160 --> 00:13:26.160
[Unknown]: Wow.

00:13:26.160 --> 00:13:30.520
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, there was a tiny village, but it was really tiny fisherman's village. Now

00:13:30.520 --> 00:13:37.800
[Guest]: it's quite different because it's developed like most places. But we could virtually,

00:13:37.800 --> 00:13:46.320
[Guest]: in fact, our kind of preference as we climbed the ladder in the college was to find a room

00:13:46.320 --> 00:13:52.840
[Guest]: from which we could see the sea, you know. So that was an incredible experience to have

00:13:52.840 --> 00:13:53.840
[Amit Varma]: that.

00:13:53.840 --> 00:13:55.400
[Amit Varma]: And you didn't get a room where you could see the sea?

00:13:55.400 --> 00:14:00.640
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah. Most of the time. Because you go on the higher floor, second or third or

00:14:00.640 --> 00:14:05.880
[Guest]: fourth floor, you'll see the sea. The sea was just there. So, and the breeze, you could

00:14:05.880 --> 00:14:15.160
[Guest]: always smell the sea. So that was really the most memorable college experience because

00:14:15.160 --> 00:14:20.160
[Guest]: I was a mediocre student. I mean, like we all had to finish and we had to look for,

00:14:20.160 --> 00:14:27.320
[Guest]: you know, all the public sector exams for jobs, etc, etc. Yeah, so that was, but I do

00:14:27.320 --> 00:14:32.640
[Guest]: my, my, I mean, apart from the location, the thing I think I learned, perhaps the only

00:14:32.640 --> 00:14:39.120
[Guest]: thing I learned or I still remember and use perhaps is, you know, engineering is about

00:14:39.120 --> 00:14:43.760
[Guest]: solving problems. I try to look at what's the problem, how to break it down, how to

00:14:43.760 --> 00:14:52.440
[Guest]: figure out the steps to go around it. And that, to me, I think has been the real education

00:14:52.440 --> 00:14:58.920
[Guest]: that I think I'm very pleased or very grateful about, that I didn't know it'll turn out

00:14:58.920 --> 00:15:05.400
[Guest]: this way. But that's something I've used perhaps right through, I mean, for the last

00:15:05.400 --> 00:15:14.000
[Guest]: 30, 30 plus years, yeah. So that I think has been, so I'm still carrying that sense all

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:19.800
[Guest]: the time in my mind, that I can perhaps look at things somewhat differently and figure

00:15:19.800 --> 00:15:24.240
[Guest]: out how to go around it and gives me, and that's my only satisfaction, that if I can

00:15:24.240 --> 00:15:29.520
[Guest]: find out something that I had not thought before, that I had not come across before

00:15:29.520 --> 00:15:36.280
[Guest]: and get a handle on it. To me, there's nothing more satisfying than that. So it's, yeah,

00:15:36.280 --> 00:15:41.600
[Guest]: it's a completely personal, personal trip. So, which is why, you know, there's no book

00:15:41.600 --> 00:15:42.600
[Guest]: to showcase.

00:15:42.600 --> 00:15:47.720
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, as you were speaking of your school in Madhya Pradesh, the thought struck

00:15:47.720 --> 00:15:51.480
[Amit Varma]: me that in a sense, and I'll explain what I mean by that, in a sense, we're all born

00:15:51.480 --> 00:15:56.040
[Amit Varma]: blind in the sense that we don't really have a way of seeing the world when we are

00:15:56.040 --> 00:16:00.040
[Amit Varma]: kids. And when we begin to see the world, we are blind to a lot of things because we

00:16:00.040 --> 00:16:04.880
[Amit Varma]: haven't kind of experienced them. Like it strikes me that you're not knowing English

00:16:04.880 --> 00:16:09.200
[Amit Varma]: or Hindi, and the teachers spending that time with you, being compassionate, reaching out

00:16:09.200 --> 00:16:15.200
[Amit Varma]: to you, empathizing, understanding, you know, for, she must have had that extra layer of

00:16:15.200 --> 00:16:19.960
[Amit Varma]: empathy for someone who is not one of her kids in the sense, not from there. And equally

00:16:19.960 --> 00:16:27.680
[Amit Varma]: for you, at some level, it must have also made you more aware in your later life, wherever

00:16:27.680 --> 00:16:31.920
[Amit Varma]: that there are people around you who may not see things the same way, who may be unfortunate

00:16:31.920 --> 00:16:36.400
[Amit Varma]: in different ways, and they don't need to be condemned or cast aside, but helped and

00:16:36.400 --> 00:16:40.720
[Amit Varma]: all that. And, you know, one of your qualities as our mutual friend, Mohit and I were discussing

00:16:40.720 --> 00:16:46.760
[Amit Varma]: last night is your incredible compassion for people you don't even know. And for all the

00:16:46.760 --> 00:16:50.680
[Amit Varma]: other kids, it might not have been like that. They may have completely ignored you and not

00:16:50.680 --> 00:16:54.260
[Amit Varma]: given a shit because they haven't had that experience. Like I look at myself growing

00:16:54.260 --> 00:16:59.880
[Amit Varma]: up also in a cocoon of privilege, and I was blind to a lot of things and you grow older

00:16:59.880 --> 00:17:05.720
[Amit Varma]: and experience a world and more and more layers kind of fall off. And I'm just thinking aloud

00:17:05.720 --> 00:17:11.880
[Amit Varma]: here. But how much do you think there is something to that in the sense that people can be innately

00:17:11.880 --> 00:17:18.520
[Amit Varma]: compassionate and empathetic, I mean, to lesser or greater extents, or experiences can play

00:17:18.520 --> 00:17:24.920
[Amit Varma]: a big part in them seeing the world a little differently or making an effort to see the

00:17:24.920 --> 00:17:31.640
[Amit Varma]: world a little differently in this way. And the reason I ask this is that too often, through

00:17:31.640 --> 00:17:36.200
[Amit Varma]: our lives, as thinkers, as people wrestling with ideologies or ways of looking at the

00:17:36.200 --> 00:17:41.680
[Amit Varma]: world, too often, I think me and many other people I know, have made the mistake of thinking

00:17:41.680 --> 00:17:47.480
[Amit Varma]: at of everything at an intellectual level. And one of the things that I am still learning

00:17:47.480 --> 00:17:53.120
[Amit Varma]: from you is that don't think about ideas, think about people, everything is really about

00:17:53.120 --> 00:17:57.800
[Amit Varma]: people and reaching out and connecting, which you are so good at doing. So bit of a ramble,

00:17:57.800 --> 00:18:00.720
[Amit Varma]: but what are your sort of thoughts on this?

00:18:00.720 --> 00:18:09.400
[Guest]: It's interesting you put it that way. I probably wouldn't or probably that wasn't my kind

00:18:09.400 --> 00:18:13.760
[Guest]: of direct experience. Well, you know, I am grateful to everything that has happened in

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:27.720
[Guest]: the past and most of which I had no control. But I think, you know, for instance, after

00:18:27.720 --> 00:18:34.400
[Guest]: my initial first 20 years, since I thought, and that was one of my reasons to explore

00:18:34.400 --> 00:18:40.560
[Guest]: public policy, was that I'd look into things that I am interested in, that I had not done

00:18:40.560 --> 00:18:47.680
[Guest]: before. And to me, that was my biggest kind of stimulus that you can venture into any

00:18:47.680 --> 00:18:54.320
[Guest]: issue because as a citizen, as a member of the public, you must have a handle to it.

00:18:54.320 --> 00:19:02.200
[Guest]: And which I realized very late, although I experienced it for since about 2000 on. But

00:19:02.200 --> 00:19:11.440
[Guest]: I realized it only in the last five years, perhaps, that we forget the public part of

00:19:11.440 --> 00:19:12.440
[Guest]: the policy.

00:19:12.440 --> 00:19:16.480
[Guest]: Public policy, when you're saying before the policy, consider the public.

00:19:16.480 --> 00:19:22.200
[Guest]: We forget the prefix, you know, it's always there. It's always, you know, the phrase is

00:19:22.200 --> 00:19:27.400
[Guest]: public policy, but we forget the public and we focus on the policy and we think, you know,

00:19:27.400 --> 00:19:34.440
[Guest]: we are doing the best job we can, we are preparing the most rational, most contextual policy

00:19:34.440 --> 00:19:39.280
[Guest]: we can think of, and the public will just lap it, accept it, because after all, what's

00:19:39.280 --> 00:19:41.800
[Guest]: the public?

00:19:41.800 --> 00:19:48.000
[Guest]: I think that has been one of, I mean, as of now, I'm sure it may change as I go along.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:57.520
[Guest]: As of now, that has been kind of my realization, which was a conscious realization because,

00:19:57.520 --> 00:20:03.640
[Guest]: I mean, whatever is innate or whatever was seen normal, I wouldn't be aware of it as

00:20:03.640 --> 00:20:05.200
[Guest]: such.

00:20:05.200 --> 00:20:11.280
[Guest]: But last five, six years, I've become really aware that where we went wrong.

00:20:11.280 --> 00:20:16.600
[Guest]: And I think, and I mean, not just me, but I think what you just said a little earlier,

00:20:16.600 --> 00:20:29.840
[Guest]: that the intellectual discourse has a tendency to create a sense of knowledge and an imperceptible

00:20:29.840 --> 00:20:39.560
[Guest]: sense of arrogance, which I have tried, at least consciously, tried to break down and

00:20:39.560 --> 00:20:42.320
[Guest]: challenge myself, at least in the last five, six years.

00:20:42.320 --> 00:20:47.120
[Guest]: Every time I kind of felt that, you know, I think I know.

00:20:47.120 --> 00:20:55.120
[Guest]: So the moment I feel that I think I know something, I try to push to see, is there all to it or

00:20:55.120 --> 00:20:58.080
[Guest]: is there a way to look beyond?

00:20:58.080 --> 00:21:05.680
[Guest]: And I think that is, I think has been a real realization that why we made the mistake and

00:21:05.680 --> 00:21:09.680
[Guest]: which is what I've been very provocative, even before that, when I was kind of grappling

00:21:09.680 --> 00:21:16.920
[Guest]: with this, that, you know, among the kind of circles I was in, education and awareness

00:21:16.920 --> 00:21:25.160
[Guest]: was a big thing, that we need to make people aware, make people, educate people.

00:21:25.160 --> 00:21:32.680
[Guest]: And to me, that itself carries in it the seed of arrogance and therefore the blindness to

00:21:32.680 --> 00:21:42.200
[Guest]: people because a teacher is supposed to know and communicate that and make the student

00:21:42.200 --> 00:21:47.600
[Guest]: who is kind of innocent or ignorant aware of the so-called issues.

00:21:47.600 --> 00:21:51.420
[Guest]: But that I think is only half the story.

00:21:51.420 --> 00:21:59.680
[Guest]: If the teacher can't relate to the student or if the teacher can't place the issue in

00:21:59.680 --> 00:22:04.760
[Guest]: the context or through the lens through which the student might be seeing it, no amount

00:22:04.760 --> 00:22:08.720
[Guest]: of education and awareness is going to help.

00:22:08.720 --> 00:22:18.960
[Guest]: So all this came to me much later because I began to kind of ask at many meetings that

00:22:18.960 --> 00:22:19.960
[Guest]: what are we teaching?

00:22:19.960 --> 00:22:22.280
[Guest]: To whom are we teaching?

00:22:22.280 --> 00:22:29.360
[Guest]: Is it because we know or is it because every opportunity is an occasion for us to know

00:22:29.360 --> 00:22:32.560
[Guest]: a little bit more?

00:22:32.560 --> 00:22:41.640
[Guest]: You know, that puts me in a kind of a jeopardy because I tend to always think on my feet.

00:22:41.640 --> 00:22:49.760
[Guest]: I like that and therefore even when I prepare a text, I deviate because if I prepared it,

00:22:49.760 --> 00:22:50.760
[Guest]: I know it.

00:22:50.760 --> 00:22:57.640
[Guest]: You know, I need to push no matter what I am trying and that comes with its risk because

00:22:57.640 --> 00:23:01.600
[Guest]: I may not know where I am headed.

00:23:01.600 --> 00:23:10.320
[Guest]: But to me the satisfaction is that at the end if I make a mistake, I hope I try to recognize

00:23:10.320 --> 00:23:14.360
[Guest]: it so that I can rectify it and take that one more step.

00:23:14.360 --> 00:23:21.400
[Guest]: And if I think I put the thing in a way that satisfied me, then perhaps I have a base to

00:23:21.400 --> 00:23:22.400
[Guest]: build further.

00:23:22.400 --> 00:23:28.960
[Guest]: So I look at it as a win-win, you know, no matter what happens and which to me actually

00:23:28.960 --> 00:23:38.240
[Guest]: has kind of helped I believe that currently or last few years, I actually try to go out

00:23:38.240 --> 00:23:44.360
[Guest]: and engage with not just people I didn't know but engage with people or try to reach

00:23:44.360 --> 00:23:52.320
[Guest]: out to people with whom I might actually have a disagreement and figure out how do I learn

00:23:52.320 --> 00:23:59.680
[Guest]: to communicate, to have a meaningful discussion, dialogue with people with whom both of us

00:23:59.680 --> 00:24:05.160
[Guest]: may know that we disagree on some things and disagreements can be quite fundamental in

00:24:05.160 --> 00:24:12.880
[Guest]: terms of ideology or intellectual perspectives but yet have a conversation which is another

00:24:12.880 --> 00:24:17.480
[Guest]: way of saying that that's another way for me to push myself.

00:24:17.480 --> 00:24:24.120
[Guest]: But how do I and in today's context it becomes even much more relevant because 10-15 years

00:24:24.120 --> 00:24:28.320
[Guest]: ago there was no eco-chamber to speak of as such, you know.

00:24:28.320 --> 00:24:33.800
[Guest]: So today's context, I mean to me there can't be anything much more fundamental than figuring

00:24:33.800 --> 00:24:42.720
[Guest]: out how do we break out from our own cocoons, own, you know, safe zones and really have

00:24:42.720 --> 00:24:47.760
[Guest]: some exciting things to do, to learn, to push, yeah.

00:24:47.760 --> 00:24:55.040
[Guest]: So that I think which is probably why I'm interested in people because it always puts

00:24:55.040 --> 00:24:58.800
[Guest]: me in a new situation because everybody is different, you know, everybody is looking

00:24:58.800 --> 00:25:05.320
[Guest]: at the world through a different lens than mine even those who may agree with me on very

00:25:05.320 --> 00:25:07.920
[Guest]: many things.

00:25:07.920 --> 00:25:15.480
[Guest]: So I think that's quite an exciting way of taking the next step, yeah.

00:25:15.480 --> 00:25:20.480
[Amit Varma]: So yesterday I recorded an episode with Abhinandan Sekri, the News Laundry founder that'll probably

00:25:20.480 --> 00:25:25.360
[Amit Varma]: come out a few weeks before this one and in that he said something very interesting.

00:25:25.360 --> 00:25:29.280
[Amit Varma]: He spoke about how while shooting for a television show he was going through the Northeast and

00:25:29.280 --> 00:25:33.440
[Amit Varma]: in the Northeast when they were in these different villages, they asked the people that, you

00:25:33.440 --> 00:25:36.800
[Amit Varma]: know, if the government is to spend money on you or if you have money to spend, what

00:25:36.800 --> 00:25:38.280
[Amit Varma]: would you spend it on?

00:25:38.280 --> 00:25:41.800
[Amit Varma]: And the answers he said that we were expecting in all our arrogance, we thought they will

00:25:41.800 --> 00:25:45.640
[Amit Varma]: say roads or infrastructure or bridges or whatever.

00:25:45.640 --> 00:25:48.840
[Amit Varma]: And they said, make a cinema theater or make a dance hall.

00:25:48.840 --> 00:25:54.300
[Amit Varma]: And he said his initial reaction was one of a sort of a patronizing looking down on these

00:25:54.300 --> 00:25:57.120
[Amit Varma]: people that don't they understand their greater good?

00:25:57.120 --> 00:25:58.760
[Amit Varma]: Why do they want a cinema hall?

00:25:58.760 --> 00:26:02.440
[Amit Varma]: But then when he spoke to them deeper, he realized that what was behind it was as a

00:26:02.440 --> 00:26:06.040
[Amit Varma]: young people were growing up, they wanted to see movies because there was nothing in

00:26:06.040 --> 00:26:08.640
[Amit Varma]: their own village or town where they could see movies.

00:26:08.640 --> 00:26:11.920
[Amit Varma]: They would go to other cities like whatever, Imphal, Shillong, whatever is the nearest

00:26:11.920 --> 00:26:12.920
[Amit Varma]: big city.

00:26:12.920 --> 00:26:16.080
[Amit Varma]: And the roads were so bad that an accident rates were so high.

00:26:16.080 --> 00:26:18.720
[Amit Varma]: The death rate was pretty high just going to watch a film.

00:26:18.720 --> 00:26:20.760
[Amit Varma]: What if the cinema theater was in the village itself?

00:26:20.760 --> 00:26:24.600
[Amit Varma]: Now, this is something no central planner from a distance can foresee.

00:26:24.600 --> 00:26:30.400
[Amit Varma]: So if you go with the arrogance of a public policy person and you say externalities, roads

00:26:30.400 --> 00:26:36.520
[Amit Varma]: or from another point of view, you might say then they will vote for us if we build a temple

00:26:36.520 --> 00:26:37.720
[Amit Varma]: for the gods.

00:26:37.720 --> 00:26:43.560
[Amit Varma]: But actually, locally, what people may want individuals in a community they want is completely

00:26:43.560 --> 00:26:44.560
[Amit Varma]: different.

00:26:44.560 --> 00:26:49.200
[Amit Varma]: And as you were saying that it just reminded me of the wiseness of that, that even though

00:26:49.200 --> 00:26:54.040
[Amit Varma]: you're an engineer, you thankfully don't have what we derisively call the engineering mindset,

00:26:54.040 --> 00:26:58.600
[Amit Varma]: which is that thing that you can design a society or you can design an intervention

00:26:58.600 --> 00:27:03.280
[Amit Varma]: in particular ways, assuming that people are a static thing, but people are not a static

00:27:03.280 --> 00:27:04.280
[Amit Varma]: thing.

00:27:04.280 --> 00:27:10.600
[Amit Varma]: Their needs and desires are very local, very specific and inaccessible to outsiders.

00:27:10.600 --> 00:27:16.800
[Amit Varma]: So tell me something, this realization of yours, which I'm beginning to think about

00:27:16.800 --> 00:27:20.600
[Amit Varma]: seriously and realizing myself and just by talking to you learning from that must have

00:27:20.600 --> 00:27:24.120
[Amit Varma]: happened over a period of many years.

00:27:24.120 --> 00:27:28.720
[Amit Varma]: So can you, for example, think of mistakes in your thinking, assumptions you made at

00:27:28.720 --> 00:27:33.800
[Amit Varma]: some point, perhaps, which got corrected when you actually, you know, met with people like

00:27:33.800 --> 00:27:38.640
[Amit Varma]: moments where you thought, oh, my thinking was arrogant and wrong and simplistic.

00:27:38.640 --> 00:27:42.520
[Amit Varma]: And now I know better because I made the effort to kind of reach out.

00:27:42.520 --> 00:27:47.120
[Amit Varma]: So can you give me like instances of that so I can understand how the process went?

00:27:47.120 --> 00:27:50.200
[Guest]: Yeah, it was like you said, it was long drawn.

00:27:50.200 --> 00:27:55.880
[Guest]: I mean, obviously, there was no kind of a sunrise moment that it happens.

00:27:55.880 --> 00:28:07.640
[Guest]: I mean, primarily it was that when we started or when I started in the late 80s, early 90s,

00:28:07.640 --> 00:28:18.360
[Guest]: India was liberalizing and we didn't know where we will head.

00:28:18.360 --> 00:28:24.360
[Guest]: But by that time, I had kind of a clearer idea where I would like to head.

00:28:24.360 --> 00:28:30.480
[Guest]: And therefore, public policy greatly interested me in the hope that it will shape the tomorrow

00:28:30.480 --> 00:28:31.480
[Guest]: or the future.

00:28:31.480 --> 00:28:45.120
[Guest]: So in that early 90s, the issue primarily as I see it now was, how do I win the debate?

00:28:45.120 --> 00:28:50.200
[Guest]: You know, how do I score the points that I want to score so that the other side is kind

00:28:50.200 --> 00:28:54.680
[Guest]: of beaten back?

00:28:54.680 --> 00:29:05.960
[Guest]: Over the next 10-15 years, I realized that that is one of the fundamental flaws.

00:29:05.960 --> 00:29:08.440
[Guest]: It's not about defeating the other side.

00:29:08.440 --> 00:29:11.480
[Guest]: It's about winning over the other side.

00:29:11.480 --> 00:29:17.760
[Guest]: You know, so to me, that became, I mean, again, this realization didn't happen overnight.

00:29:17.760 --> 00:29:26.160
[Guest]: But as I see it, it began to happen about 10-15 years since I began.

00:29:26.160 --> 00:29:31.840
[Guest]: And one critical point, which I again, which I didn't realize, which happened 20 years

00:29:31.840 --> 00:29:39.120
[Guest]: ago, but I actually didn't realize its significance since I'm looking back now.

00:29:39.120 --> 00:29:46.480
[Guest]: It was in 2000 and when I was really active, I mean, you know, I mean, the climate change

00:29:46.480 --> 00:29:53.040
[Guest]: or the WTO or whatever, where a liberal angle could be placed and where I could be as provocative,

00:29:53.040 --> 00:29:54.040
[Guest]: I would be as provocative.

00:29:54.040 --> 00:29:57.480
[Guest]: I mean, for the sake of scoring that point.

00:29:57.480 --> 00:30:05.440
[Guest]: So I wrote and spoke on things which would be outlandish even today.

00:30:05.440 --> 00:30:20.280
[Guest]: But in 2000, I happened to come across a movement that Sharad Joshi was leading at that time.

00:30:20.280 --> 00:30:24.520
[Guest]: I mean, Sharad Joshi is the farmer's leader who passed away a few years ago.

00:30:24.520 --> 00:30:29.220
[Guest]: I met him in the early 90s, so I knew him.

00:30:29.220 --> 00:30:34.320
[Guest]: But we knew each other intellectually that we had a liberal orientation, etc.

00:30:34.320 --> 00:30:41.880
[Guest]: But in 2000, I came across his first, and that was also mine, a first direct experience

00:30:41.880 --> 00:30:47.880
[Guest]: exposure even to a limited extent of a mass movement, because I did grow up during the

00:30:47.880 --> 00:30:50.640
[Guest]: anti-emergency when I just went to college.

00:30:50.640 --> 00:30:55.960
[Guest]: And I still remember the blank pages of newspapers that came on the day emergency came, when

00:30:55.960 --> 00:31:00.600
[Guest]: I was just completing my class 11.

00:31:00.600 --> 00:31:09.080
[Guest]: And therefore, I had seen that era of public enthusiasm for change, etc., etc.

00:31:09.080 --> 00:31:15.960
[Guest]: But it was in this one, in 2000, that I began to see and actually experienced it, because

00:31:15.960 --> 00:31:24.440
[Guest]: proof of the pudding is in eating, that Sharad Joshi's ability to connect with the people

00:31:24.440 --> 00:31:38.560
[Guest]: beyond the intellectual dimension actually made people aspire or get inspired to strive

00:31:38.560 --> 00:31:45.040
[Guest]: for things which otherwise they may not have, or it may have happened much later.

00:31:45.040 --> 00:31:51.120
[Guest]: And secondly, once the people connected, the policy followed.

00:31:51.120 --> 00:32:00.000
[Guest]: So that was my first direct experience on a movement that was built on the first generation

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:08.360
[Guest]: genetically modified cotton, which the cotton farmers in Western India, particularly Gujarat-Maharashtra

00:32:08.360 --> 00:32:11.800
[Guest]: and some other parts wanted.

00:32:11.800 --> 00:32:18.920
[Guest]: They were already growing the unauthorized, unapproved varieties, which is how the world

00:32:18.920 --> 00:32:23.320
[Guest]: came to know that Indian farmers were already growing something that hadn't been approved

00:32:23.320 --> 00:32:26.640
[Guest]: or authorized by the state.

00:32:26.640 --> 00:32:30.800
[Guest]: And Sharad Joshi sought to leverage that.

00:32:30.800 --> 00:32:41.320
[Guest]: And in 2002, in a matter of a month, the government changed its policy.

00:32:41.320 --> 00:32:46.840
[Guest]: To me, that was, you know, I was more an observer, but a close observer since I knew him and

00:32:46.840 --> 00:32:51.480
[Guest]: had been to some of the things, and because it was new to me, because I had never interacted

00:32:51.480 --> 00:32:56.000
[Guest]: with public in my adult life as much as then.

00:32:56.000 --> 00:33:10.000
[Guest]: So it was kind of an eye-opener that the policy could change if we can build the political

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:16.320
[Guest]: capital, and the political capital can only come if we can take the people or significant

00:33:16.320 --> 00:33:25.040
[Guest]: number of people with us, something which I had not experienced nor thought of then.

00:33:25.040 --> 00:33:35.760
[Guest]: And again, I didn't realize the full significance till over quite a few years, a decade or more.

00:33:35.760 --> 00:33:44.660
[Guest]: But to me, that was one direct personal experience that I can think of, which turned me from

00:33:44.660 --> 00:33:47.640
[Guest]: the policy to public policy, yeah.

00:33:47.640 --> 00:33:55.680
[Guest]: So for that, and Sharad Joshi not being primarily an intellectual, although he was, given his

00:33:55.680 --> 00:34:03.680
[Guest]: background, you know, extremely educated, accomplished person coming back to India to

00:34:03.680 --> 00:34:11.720
[Guest]: look into agriculture from a family who had not been in agriculture for a few generations.

00:34:11.720 --> 00:34:17.680
[Guest]: So he did it as a practitioner, you know, so he was not pursuing the issue primarily

00:34:17.680 --> 00:34:28.200
[Guest]: on the intellectual plane, which to me is my kind of lesson that intellectual dimensions

00:34:28.200 --> 00:34:33.640
[Guest]: are important, but they're not nearly the whole story.

00:34:33.640 --> 00:34:36.960
[Guest]: It's the people and how do we reach out.

00:34:36.960 --> 00:34:45.240
[Guest]: And to reach out, it becomes two ways, you know, like either you reach out patronizingly

00:34:45.240 --> 00:34:50.200
[Guest]: or you reach out more as your equal.

00:34:50.200 --> 00:34:57.040
[Guest]: You empathize with them in a way a human being ought to empathize with another person.

00:34:57.040 --> 00:35:04.080
[Guest]: And which to me is amazing that five, six years after his death, in parts of Maharashtra,

00:35:04.080 --> 00:35:13.600
[Guest]: I've been, people still give me or show me wedding cards for their daughters or sons,

00:35:13.600 --> 00:35:19.280
[Guest]: not with pictures of gods, but with pictures of Sharad Joshi, which to me is something

00:35:19.280 --> 00:35:27.040
[Guest]: amazing that people would hold someone, you know, who was merely an Rajya Sabha MP, you

00:35:27.040 --> 00:35:32.200
[Guest]: know, I mean, I don't know to how long he'll be remembered as such beyond the people who

00:35:32.200 --> 00:35:33.760
[Guest]: knew him.

00:35:33.760 --> 00:35:36.840
[Guest]: But that this could happen.

00:35:36.840 --> 00:35:41.720
[Guest]: And therefore, how did, how could this happen?

00:35:41.720 --> 00:35:49.880
[Guest]: That how do you build the relationship where this level, this depth of bonding happens

00:35:49.880 --> 00:35:55.400
[Guest]: and what a contrast it is with today, with social media and the rest, well, we are more

00:35:55.400 --> 00:35:57.280
[Guest]: connected.

00:35:57.280 --> 00:35:58.280
[Guest]: We have no connection.

00:35:58.280 --> 00:35:59.280
[Guest]: Isn't it amazing?

00:35:59.280 --> 00:36:02.320
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I feel it really amazing.

00:36:02.320 --> 00:36:06.800
[Amit Varma]: That's beautifully put, I'll just give some context to my listeners about Sharad Joshi

00:36:06.800 --> 00:36:10.560
[Amit Varma]: and the specific movement you were, you know, you witnessed up close.

00:36:10.560 --> 00:36:15.920
[Amit Varma]: Sharad Joshi was a great leader, bureaucrat, etc, etc, who essentially came back to India

00:36:15.920 --> 00:36:20.600
[Amit Varma]: in the late 70s and said, I'll go back to farming and then realized as a farmer the

00:36:20.600 --> 00:36:23.800
[Amit Varma]: problems that agriculturalists throughout the country faced.

00:36:23.800 --> 00:36:28.360
[Amit Varma]: But unlike the other political rhetoric of the day, which saw the state as a solution

00:36:28.360 --> 00:36:33.640
[Amit Varma]: to these problems, he realized that most of these problems had been created by the state

00:36:33.640 --> 00:36:38.960
[Amit Varma]: and that these counterintuitive ideas had to be communicated to the people at large.

00:36:38.960 --> 00:36:44.600
[Amit Varma]: And he managed to actually build a mass movement of farmers who were, in a sense, asking for

00:36:44.600 --> 00:36:45.880
[Amit Varma]: the state to get out of the way.

00:36:45.880 --> 00:36:50.320
[Amit Varma]: And I have a very good episode in Hindi, which kind of explains this with the leader.

00:36:50.320 --> 00:36:52.520
[Amit Varma]: You introduced me to Varun Gunwan Patil.

00:36:52.520 --> 00:36:56.520
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you were present at the recording in the room when I recorded with Gunwan ji.

00:36:56.520 --> 00:36:57.520
[Amit Varma]: So that's episode 86.

00:36:57.520 --> 00:36:59.400
[Amit Varma]: I'll link it from the show notes.

00:36:59.400 --> 00:37:03.440
[Amit Varma]: And I also wrote a column called A Tale of Two Satyagrahas.

00:37:03.440 --> 00:37:07.480
[Amit Varma]: And one of them was the one that you speak of, that essentially, just to give context

00:37:07.480 --> 00:37:13.440
[Amit Varma]: again, in the 1990s, as the 90s were coming to an end, cotton crops across India started

00:37:13.440 --> 00:37:17.580
[Amit Varma]: failing because there were pests like bollworms that were ravaging these crops.

00:37:17.580 --> 00:37:22.400
[Amit Varma]: And farmers had to use increasing amounts of pesticide to keep them at bay.

00:37:22.400 --> 00:37:26.120
[Amit Varma]: And there was so much more labor involved, the cost of the pesticides were high.

00:37:26.120 --> 00:37:28.160
[Amit Varma]: The crops would often fail anyway.

00:37:28.160 --> 00:37:30.160
[Amit Varma]: It was just a downward spiral.

00:37:30.160 --> 00:37:31.800
[Amit Varma]: Then technology.

00:37:31.800 --> 00:37:35.960
[Amit Varma]: Farmers heard of something called BT cotton, which was a genetically modified kind of cotton.

00:37:35.960 --> 00:37:39.920
[Amit Varma]: And it was being used across the world, completely safe.

00:37:39.920 --> 00:37:44.480
[Amit Varma]: But because it's a new technology, Luddites everywhere were kind of protesting and they

00:37:44.480 --> 00:37:46.400
[Amit Varma]: were illegal in India.

00:37:46.400 --> 00:37:50.920
[Amit Varma]: So then what happened is farmers in Gujarat got hold of a bunch of these BT cotton seeds

00:37:50.920 --> 00:37:52.480
[Amit Varma]: and they planted them.

00:37:52.480 --> 00:37:59.400
[Amit Varma]: And what happened in 2002 was that all cotton crops in Gujarat failed, except the 10,000

00:37:59.400 --> 00:38:01.800
[Amit Varma]: acres with BT cotton.

00:38:01.800 --> 00:38:04.160
[Amit Varma]: You would imagine that there would be a lesson in this.

00:38:04.160 --> 00:38:08.560
[Amit Varma]: But the lesson that the government took was not that these are the crops that survived,

00:38:08.560 --> 00:38:11.080
[Amit Varma]: but that these are the crops which are illegal.

00:38:11.080 --> 00:38:15.200
[Amit Varma]: So they wanted to burn these 10,000 hectares of cotton.

00:38:15.200 --> 00:38:20.120
[Amit Varma]: And at this point, Sharad Joshi, who leads the Shetkari Sangatana in Maharashtra, took

00:38:20.120 --> 00:38:25.320
[Amit Varma]: around 10,000 farmers with him to Gujarat to stand with their fellow farmers.

00:38:25.320 --> 00:38:28.520
[Amit Varma]: And they basically just went into those fields and they said, you want to take the cotton

00:38:28.520 --> 00:38:31.240
[Amit Varma]: over our dead bodies, come and do it.

00:38:31.240 --> 00:38:35.400
[Amit Varma]: And like you said, the people's movement there was just too much.

00:38:35.400 --> 00:38:41.040
[Amit Varma]: And the ban on BT cotton was lifted by the Vajpayee government, which is such an inspiring

00:38:41.040 --> 00:38:42.560
[Amit Varma]: story at many levels.

00:38:42.560 --> 00:38:47.960
[Amit Varma]: Like, I think I've seen a clip of you at a press conference of farmers in 1999 or something,

00:38:47.960 --> 00:38:48.960
[Guest]: right?

00:38:48.960 --> 00:38:55.720
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, where, you know, a distant clip where you are also holding forth on this.

00:38:55.720 --> 00:39:00.160
[Amit Varma]: And by the way, I'll put a link to my column, which kind of talks about why, you know, GMO

00:39:00.160 --> 00:39:02.400
[Amit Varma]: is great, fantastic, we should embrace it.

00:39:02.400 --> 00:39:07.520
[Amit Varma]: Now, let's go a little further back in your journey that we've spoken of public policy,

00:39:07.520 --> 00:39:11.160
[Amit Varma]: we've spoken of policy and we've spoken of public policy, as you said, but before this,

00:39:11.160 --> 00:39:14.040
[Amit Varma]: you were a marine engineer and you sailed the world.

00:39:14.040 --> 00:39:16.880
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, post your engineering and all that.

00:39:16.880 --> 00:39:21.920
[Amit Varma]: Tell me about those sort of experiences like at that time when you were in college in RSC

00:39:21.920 --> 00:39:24.920
[Amit Varma]: Suratkal doing engineering and so on.

00:39:24.920 --> 00:39:25.920
[Amit Varma]: What did you want to be?

00:39:25.920 --> 00:39:27.200
[Amit Varma]: What was your view of the world?

00:39:27.200 --> 00:39:32.280
[Amit Varma]: And in ideological terms, how was your view of the world sort of developing?

00:39:32.280 --> 00:39:37.780
[Amit Varma]: Because I remember, I didn't think the things I think today when I was 20 or even 25.

00:39:37.780 --> 00:39:42.560
[Amit Varma]: It took a lot of time for me to gradually come around to my way of thinking.

00:39:42.560 --> 00:39:47.840
[Amit Varma]: And otherwise, it was very vague in college, I was just all over the place, no fixed ideas

00:39:47.840 --> 00:39:52.160
[Amit Varma]: on anything, which is not surprising, because the received wisdom around you is so flawed

00:39:52.160 --> 00:39:55.600
[Amit Varma]: in so many ways, with the religion of the state and so on.

00:39:55.600 --> 00:39:59.440
[Amit Varma]: And also, you have so few books to read, though I was more privileged than most, but you have,

00:39:59.440 --> 00:40:02.240
[Amit Varma]: you just don't have that kind of access and exposure.

00:40:02.240 --> 00:40:08.440
[Amit Varma]: So give me a sense of your intellectual development through that early period and how the way

00:40:08.440 --> 00:40:12.000
[Amit Varma]: you look at the world begins to change.

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:17.240
[Guest]: I mean, I grew up in, like I said, I grew up in a family which was very political.

00:40:17.240 --> 00:40:21.320
[Guest]: From both sides, from my father's side and from my mother's side.

00:40:21.320 --> 00:40:26.120
[Guest]: Although part of my, from my mother's side was on, in the left, quite actively involved

00:40:26.120 --> 00:40:32.440
[Guest]: with left politics in Bengal, and my father's side and my maternal grandfather, they were

00:40:32.440 --> 00:40:37.920
[Guest]: all deeply into Congress from, you know, almost the time they were born.

00:40:37.920 --> 00:40:40.400
[Guest]: And my father continued in that vein.

00:40:40.400 --> 00:40:45.080
[Guest]: So I grew up, so it was natural that, you know, I grew up in a family that would be

00:40:45.080 --> 00:40:51.760
[Guest]: anti-CPM or left in Bengal and Congress.

00:40:51.760 --> 00:41:00.120
[Guest]: But then I saw my father change during 77 or 76, I mean, emergency time.

00:41:00.120 --> 00:41:05.520
[Guest]: And that was just the excitement, you know, like it was a David versus Goliath thing for

00:41:05.520 --> 00:41:06.520
[Guest]: me.

00:41:06.520 --> 00:41:11.200
[Guest]: I mean, more than because I didn't really have a full grasp of emergency except the

00:41:11.200 --> 00:41:17.040
[Guest]: blank spaces I saw in Statesman in Calcutta that, you know, the printed blank spaces because

00:41:17.040 --> 00:41:18.040
[Guest]: of censorship.

00:41:18.040 --> 00:41:24.600
[Guest]: So apart from that, I don't really have a direct, this thing except for occasional columns,

00:41:24.600 --> 00:41:29.440
[Guest]: Minoo Masani or things that would interest me, that's something different, something

00:41:29.440 --> 00:41:32.760
[Guest]: to think about, or something that made me think.

00:41:32.760 --> 00:41:45.080
[Guest]: But I think what happened was or how it happened perhaps is the emergency and the turmoil and

00:41:45.080 --> 00:41:51.680
[Guest]: the best part of that turmoil was perhaps that it happened in the physical space, you

00:41:51.680 --> 00:41:59.080
[Guest]: know, having and seeing how the social media space or the digital space, the behavior takes

00:41:59.080 --> 00:42:00.320
[Guest]: place.

00:42:00.320 --> 00:42:07.120
[Guest]: I think my initial experience were all in the physical space, so while we had less access

00:42:07.120 --> 00:42:15.320
[Guest]: to books and there was no internet in the 80s, but we did, and I actually, I mean, me,

00:42:15.320 --> 00:42:20.040
[Guest]: my brothers, we came up from a family which read a lot, you know, I was, I remember books

00:42:20.040 --> 00:42:25.000
[Guest]: and comics and things of every kind in our household from my birth.

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:31.960
[Guest]: And my mother used to feed me anything that she thought I could read, and all of our brothers,

00:42:31.960 --> 00:42:33.560
[Guest]: we read a lot.

00:42:33.560 --> 00:42:40.400
[Guest]: So reading was natural and therefore in the 80s, while we didn't have direct access or

00:42:40.400 --> 00:42:47.080
[Guest]: a quick access, because of this physical involvement or presence, because we happened to be in

00:42:47.080 --> 00:42:52.400
[Guest]: a situation where there is so much foment and turmoil, you know, emergency, then Mrs.

00:42:52.400 --> 00:42:57.840
[Guest]: Gandhi's assassination, you know, I mean, there was always turmoil, a major ones.

00:42:57.840 --> 00:43:06.320
[Guest]: And which invariably makes one, at least made me curious to look and read to try to figure

00:43:06.320 --> 00:43:10.360
[Guest]: out what's happening all around, because it's happening all around, literally.

00:43:10.360 --> 00:43:15.320
[Guest]: For instance, you know, I still remember that when Indira Gandhi was assassinated in 84,

00:43:15.320 --> 00:43:22.280
[Guest]: I was in a village in Sundarbans, and we were stuck for a week, because all connections

00:43:22.280 --> 00:43:24.400
[Guest]: were broken.

00:43:24.400 --> 00:43:29.680
[Guest]: But people were taking out rallies with, you know, chanting Indira's name and the flag

00:43:29.680 --> 00:43:37.120
[Guest]: and all the rest, even in a remote village, which had no electricity, no toilets.

00:43:37.120 --> 00:43:44.280
[Guest]: So you know, and that kind of made me wonder, and I came from a world which was very urban,

00:43:44.280 --> 00:43:48.000
[Guest]: you know, I grew up completely in urban India.

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:54.640
[Guest]: So to grow up, to experience that, and to think that how different we can be and how

00:43:54.640 --> 00:44:04.580
[Guest]: do we survive in such diverse situations, the marine engineering experience actually

00:44:04.580 --> 00:44:12.040
[Guest]: only expanded that, because I joined the marine engineering primarily as my incentive was

00:44:12.040 --> 00:44:16.960
[Guest]: to see the world at no cost, because I was not as intelligent as my brother, who could

00:44:16.960 --> 00:44:21.360
[Guest]: go to an IIT and go to US for his higher studies.

00:44:21.360 --> 00:44:26.400
[Guest]: And therefore, I had to be satisfied with less, and therefore, I thought marine engineering

00:44:26.400 --> 00:44:30.720
[Guest]: would at least give me a chance to see the world at no cost, which it did.

00:44:30.720 --> 00:44:41.600
[Guest]: But that, of course, actually increased my sense of curiosity or inquisitiveness or at

00:44:41.600 --> 00:44:42.600
[Guest]: the gulf.

00:44:42.600 --> 00:44:48.920
[Guest]: You know, so I remember one of my first letters to my mother from one of the ports I visited

00:44:48.920 --> 00:44:55.560
[Guest]: was particularly a western port in Canada, that it does look like you see in Bollywood

00:44:55.560 --> 00:44:56.560
[Guest]: films.

00:44:56.560 --> 00:45:01.640
[Guest]: You know, till that time, I had no realization actually, because in our home, we didn't

00:45:01.640 --> 00:45:03.760
[Guest]: have television till after 84-85.

00:45:03.760 --> 00:45:10.840
[Guest]: So we had experience of the outer world primarily through films, you know, as a visual medium.

00:45:10.840 --> 00:45:16.320
[Guest]: And the Bollywood was one kind, and we all knew that Bollywood either depicts things

00:45:16.320 --> 00:45:24.680
[Guest]: that are too harsh, you know, the realistic ones, or are too fantastic.

00:45:24.680 --> 00:45:30.440
[Guest]: But the harsh ones are something we don't directly experience, most of us, we haven't.

00:45:30.440 --> 00:45:33.680
[Guest]: And the fantasy ones, we can only imagine.

00:45:33.680 --> 00:45:41.600
[Guest]: Whereas in the West, in Canada, I found that the roads, the people are actually as what

00:45:41.600 --> 00:45:42.600
[Guest]: you see in the films.

00:45:42.600 --> 00:45:49.400
[Guest]: So that kind of was an eye-opener, that how could it be so different?

00:45:49.400 --> 00:45:53.960
[Guest]: And that was probably my first introduction coupled with this experience in the village

00:45:53.960 --> 00:46:01.000
[Guest]: after that for a few years, that there is something going on that we need to grapple

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:02.000
[Guest]: with.

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:05.840
[Guest]: You know, that why is this gulf?

00:46:05.840 --> 00:46:12.680
[Guest]: Why is this gulf that my brother who could get admitted in the US and spend next 25 years

00:46:12.680 --> 00:46:24.080
[Guest]: working for multinationals, could be an Indian, enjoy the Western standards, yet the family

00:46:24.080 --> 00:46:31.600
[Guest]: and the community and the country is a century perhaps behind, in every which way, not just

00:46:31.600 --> 00:46:36.320
[Guest]: financially, economically, but every which way, why?

00:46:36.320 --> 00:46:44.920
[Guest]: So that was my kind of quest into actually trying to understand public policy as such.

00:46:44.920 --> 00:46:52.840
[Guest]: And something that happened, which again, reflectively we know, because one of the stand-alone

00:46:52.840 --> 00:46:57.720
[Guest]: thing about emergency is the Nasbandi, which everybody almost in North India, or perhaps

00:46:57.720 --> 00:47:03.440
[Guest]: all over India knew, even as a youngster, I knew that something was happening, because

00:47:03.440 --> 00:47:04.440
[Guest]: everybody talked about it.

00:47:04.440 --> 00:47:10.480
[Guest]: So it was there, which basically was apart from the policy aspect of it, or the physical

00:47:10.480 --> 00:47:19.640
[Guest]: torture and the grossness of it, the policy aspect of it was that population is a challenge.

00:47:19.640 --> 00:47:23.840
[Guest]: And which would seem that population is indeed a challenge, how can you deal with people,

00:47:23.840 --> 00:47:28.320
[Guest]: with so many people growing, etc.

00:47:28.320 --> 00:47:34.120
[Guest]: That's when primarily one kind of another piece fell in place.

00:47:34.120 --> 00:47:39.360
[Guest]: Because I used to read, I sometimes, or quite often actually, whenever I could, I could

00:47:39.360 --> 00:47:45.400
[Guest]: visit British Council or American Library in Calcutta, just to read what's happening

00:47:45.400 --> 00:47:48.400
[Guest]: elsewhere.

00:47:48.400 --> 00:47:57.840
[Guest]: And I discovered Julian Simon, that was in 1986-87, just an accident, no one had told

00:47:57.840 --> 00:48:02.880
[Guest]: me anything about that.

00:48:02.880 --> 00:48:08.400
[Guest]: And I found he was a man who was arguing something very different.

00:48:08.400 --> 00:48:19.920
[Guest]: And then in 1990, he won his famous bet, that while the population would increase, the prices

00:48:19.920 --> 00:48:25.320
[Guest]: of some basic commodities that were decided on, would actually decline.

00:48:25.320 --> 00:48:29.320
[Guest]: And there were some people, biologists and economists on the other side who said, since

00:48:29.320 --> 00:48:33.200
[Guest]: the population is increasing, the prices would rise.

00:48:33.200 --> 00:48:36.960
[Amit Varma]: Just to give context, the person on the other side of the bet was a guy called Paul Ehrlich,

00:48:36.960 --> 00:48:43.280
[Amit Varma]: who was a famous Luddite, who was a famous sort of Malthusian rather, and a biologist,

00:48:43.280 --> 00:48:44.280
[Amit Varma]: and all of that.

00:48:44.280 --> 00:48:47.040
[Amit Varma]: Otherwise a learned man, but completely wrong about this one subject.

00:48:47.040 --> 00:48:51.360
[Amit Varma]: And so Julian Simon made a bet with him and said, no, growing population is a good thing

00:48:51.360 --> 00:48:52.360
[Guest]: in 1980.

00:48:52.360 --> 00:48:57.520
[Amit Varma]: And they made a bet about certain commodities, whether the prices will go up or down, where

00:48:57.520 --> 00:49:01.320
[Amit Varma]: Ehrlich said, of course, they will go up because population will go up and there'll be less

00:49:01.320 --> 00:49:02.320
[Amit Varma]: resources.

00:49:02.320 --> 00:49:04.400
[Amit Varma]: And Simon said, no, no, no, no, no, they'll go down, wait and watch.

00:49:04.400 --> 00:49:05.680
[Amit Varma]: And Simon, of course, won the bet.

00:49:05.680 --> 00:49:06.680
[Amit Varma]: Sorry, continue.

00:49:06.680 --> 00:49:12.840
[Guest]: Yeah, so that happened over, I mean, the bet was from 1980 to 1990 in the 10-year period.

00:49:12.840 --> 00:49:20.200
[Guest]: And I began to read Simon early and late 80s, I mean, just as an accident.

00:49:20.200 --> 00:49:25.160
[Guest]: And then I read the news that he's actually won the bet.

00:49:25.160 --> 00:49:27.560
[Guest]: So that was kind of a startling this thing.

00:49:27.560 --> 00:49:33.000
[Guest]: And because I was reading these at the American library, because there was no internet, I

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:37.360
[Guest]: found his address and wrote to him that this is amazing.

00:49:37.360 --> 00:49:41.560
[Guest]: And because of the past 10 years where the population, demography, etc. was such a big

00:49:41.560 --> 00:49:42.560
[Guest]: issue in India.

00:49:42.560 --> 00:49:46.760
[Guest]: So I thought that I want to know more.

00:49:46.760 --> 00:49:52.160
[Guest]: And that was kind of the single biggest spark as far as policy world is concerned, because

00:49:52.160 --> 00:49:59.240
[Guest]: before that I had no idea of public policy as such as a kind of a domain by itself.

00:49:59.240 --> 00:50:04.960
[Guest]: And Simon introduced me to the whole world of public policy and particularly free market

00:50:04.960 --> 00:50:07.560
[Guest]: public policy and free market environmentalism.

00:50:07.560 --> 00:50:17.160
[Guest]: And I kind of, my first 10 years was almost completely on how do we understand the market

00:50:17.160 --> 00:50:22.000
[Guest]: in the, or the economics in the context of environment.

00:50:22.000 --> 00:50:23.000
[Guest]: Simon wrote back to you when he wrote to you.

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:28.720
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah, he wrote back to me and I mean, we corresponded for the last eight years of

00:50:28.720 --> 00:50:32.400
[Guest]: his life.

00:50:32.400 --> 00:50:39.120
[Guest]: And he came to India, he and his wife came to India in 97, when we did our second conference,

00:50:39.120 --> 00:50:45.000
[Guest]: so called libertarian conference in Deolali in 97.

00:50:45.000 --> 00:50:47.680
[Guest]: And Simon passed away in 98.

00:50:47.680 --> 00:50:53.120
[Guest]: And before that, he'd introduced me to a whole world of free market think tanks in Europe

00:50:53.120 --> 00:50:57.360
[Guest]: and US particularly.

00:50:57.360 --> 00:51:03.640
[Guest]: So all that excited me and my interest particularly was because one, the demographic battle, the

00:51:03.640 --> 00:51:09.600
[Guest]: policy battle, which was so demonstratively won in my view as Simon won the bet.

00:51:09.600 --> 00:51:14.320
[Guest]: But from all the others that I was seeing, because environment and population is related

00:51:14.320 --> 00:51:18.800
[Guest]: to environment was such a big, I mean, it kind of interested me because I hadn't thought

00:51:18.800 --> 00:51:20.720
[Guest]: about it.

00:51:20.720 --> 00:51:26.080
[Guest]: And therefore, I thought, let's try to apply it and see.

00:51:26.080 --> 00:51:31.720
[Guest]: So that was kind of my own way of self-education that let me take the biggest challenge that

00:51:31.720 --> 00:51:36.720
[Guest]: people say it is there in terms of policy that what to do with environment.

00:51:36.720 --> 00:51:42.840
[Guest]: And let's see if my understanding or my understanding of economics of markets, which I had not studied

00:51:42.840 --> 00:51:48.640
[Guest]: at all in my through my education, I could help resolve it.

00:51:48.640 --> 00:51:53.480
[Guest]: At least in my mind, even if I don't convince anyone else and which had some interesting

00:51:53.480 --> 00:52:00.620
[Guest]: fallouts in the sense, for me personally, in the sense that I realized that being from

00:52:00.620 --> 00:52:09.120
[Guest]: outside the disciplines, neither economics nor environment, I was relatively free to

00:52:09.120 --> 00:52:17.160
[Guest]: ask anything and was only limited by my own lack of imagination or confidence.

00:52:17.160 --> 00:52:23.000
[Guest]: You know that I didn't, that I hadn't studied environment or economics in my college or

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:28.080
[Guest]: school or whatever, or any formal way, didn't kind of deter me.

00:52:28.080 --> 00:52:33.680
[Guest]: To me, because I had not studied it, I probably tried to understand it and apply it in a way

00:52:33.680 --> 00:52:40.080
[Guest]: that I could, which was kind of, you know, I mean, I think was very, very helpful.

00:52:40.080 --> 00:52:46.960
[Guest]: Because firstly, it gave me the confidence that I could think because at least in my

00:52:46.960 --> 00:52:51.160
[Guest]: mind, I thought that what I am saying makes sense to me.

00:52:51.160 --> 00:52:52.560
[Guest]: So that was very satisfying.

00:52:52.560 --> 00:53:01.800
[Guest]: Secondly, they were in the late 80s, 90s, by that time, or mid 90s, I started writing

00:53:01.800 --> 00:53:04.560
[Guest]: for newspapers, etc.

00:53:04.560 --> 00:53:09.320
[Guest]: And while the editors, etc. may not have agreed with what I am saying, but they thought it

00:53:09.320 --> 00:53:19.040
[Guest]: was new, it was different, and it was in a way related to the liberalizing tendency of

00:53:19.040 --> 00:53:21.640
[Guest]: the society and the state at that point.

00:53:21.640 --> 00:53:26.800
[Guest]: You know, the 90s was quite exciting in that sense, that people were exploring different

00:53:26.800 --> 00:53:27.800
[Guest]: issues.

00:53:27.800 --> 00:53:29.160
[Guest]: So I got some space to write.

00:53:29.160 --> 00:53:37.360
[Guest]: So that was my first, first inter, what should I say, inter-immersion into the world of public

00:53:37.360 --> 00:53:38.520
[Guest]: policy.

00:53:38.520 --> 00:53:45.680
[Guest]: But there was another thing, another turning point, I think, during my shipping days, apart

00:53:45.680 --> 00:53:52.640
[Guest]: from the gulf that I said before, was the coincidence, you know, ships generally had

00:53:52.640 --> 00:54:02.480
[Guest]: libraries and videos, VCRs, but because I was more attracted to reading, so I did.

00:54:02.480 --> 00:54:07.440
[Guest]: And one book, again, hardly, no one had actually recommended it, I just came across, which

00:54:07.440 --> 00:54:11.280
[Guest]: was Ayn Rand's Atlas Shrugged.

00:54:11.280 --> 00:54:20.160
[Guest]: So that was another of those kind of turning points in the mid 80s, that there is something

00:54:20.160 --> 00:54:21.160
[Guest]: to it.

00:54:21.160 --> 00:54:26.880
[Guest]: You know, that there is something that I need to explore which I hadn't thought of, and

00:54:26.880 --> 00:54:38.800
[Guest]: which seems to make a lot of sense in where I am, that is, in India and in our context.

00:54:38.800 --> 00:54:43.400
[Guest]: And because as I read Rand and read other things that she and others began to recommend,

00:54:43.400 --> 00:54:48.880
[Guest]: that is how I kind of accidentally came across Julian Simon, that here is something I should

00:54:48.880 --> 00:54:51.560
[Guest]: read because I thought it was interesting.

00:54:51.560 --> 00:55:02.440
[Guest]: So you know, so those mid to late 80s was a kind of two big kind of stations in my journey,

00:55:02.440 --> 00:55:11.200
[Guest]: Rand and Simon, and the next 10 years, in the 90s, I just did that.

00:55:11.200 --> 00:55:12.200
[Guest]: That how do I apply?

00:55:12.200 --> 00:55:13.200
[Guest]: How do I apply?

00:55:13.200 --> 00:55:20.240
[Guest]: And in that search, you know, we had the Liberty Institute and all the rest as a public policy

00:55:20.240 --> 00:55:27.200
[Guest]: think tank trying to copy or model on more Western think tanks.

00:55:27.200 --> 00:55:33.400
[Guest]: We are perhaps one of the very few at that time who were very, very public and gung-ho

00:55:33.400 --> 00:55:40.600
[Guest]: about liberty and free market and all the rest.

00:55:40.600 --> 00:55:49.840
[Guest]: And so 90s went, you know, I mean, was personally and extremely hectic because I was involved

00:55:49.840 --> 00:55:57.600
[Guest]: in so many issues, so many campaigns, so many policy dimensions, intellectual property,

00:55:57.600 --> 00:56:04.240
[Guest]: environment, climate change, WTO, trade, yeah, I mean, I can't think of, there was no end

00:56:04.240 --> 00:56:06.880
[Guest]: to the issues I could plunge into.

00:56:06.880 --> 00:56:11.360
[Guest]: And that was exciting, not because I knew, but it gave me an opportunity to know something

00:56:11.360 --> 00:56:16.560
[Guest]: I hadn't known before, you know, to explore that new world, new issue.

00:56:16.560 --> 00:56:22.840
[Guest]: But the next one was this Sharad Joshi's movement, which is on hindsight, which I didn't realize

00:56:22.840 --> 00:56:23.840
[Guest]: then.

00:56:23.840 --> 00:56:27.840
[Guest]: Rand and Julian Simon, I realized while I was reading that I was reading something different

00:56:27.840 --> 00:56:31.200
[Guest]: and I would like to explore it.

00:56:31.200 --> 00:56:38.800
[Guest]: Sharad Joshi's intervention in 2000-2002, at that time, I was elated that we had won

00:56:38.800 --> 00:56:43.520
[Guest]: a victory in terms of the policy dimension that the government changed its policy on

00:56:43.520 --> 00:56:51.680
[Guest]: GM Cotton and GM Cotton was approved in 2002, in February or March 2002.

00:56:51.680 --> 00:56:56.040
[Guest]: But it was more, you know, a feather in the cap, it was nothing more, I hadn't really

00:56:56.040 --> 00:57:04.760
[Guest]: grasped the public part of the policy still, which took perhaps another 10 years of struggle.

00:57:04.760 --> 00:57:10.040
[Guest]: And in that time, I was kind of getting more attracted to things that were happening on

00:57:10.040 --> 00:57:11.040
[Guest]: the people dimension.

00:57:11.040 --> 00:57:17.720
[Guest]: You know, I came to know about organizations who were acting on the ground to make things

00:57:17.720 --> 00:57:22.600
[Guest]: change and particularly their focus, because they were coming from the ground, so their

00:57:22.600 --> 00:57:29.160
[Guest]: focus was, or the starting point was the public, whereas my starting point was the policy.

00:57:29.160 --> 00:57:38.280
[Guest]: So that, you know, so one major thing or exposure for me was the Arch Vahini, you know, in Gujarat.

00:57:38.280 --> 00:57:43.640
[Guest]: I mean, I couldn't believe that I would, or I had never dreamt that I would ever come

00:57:43.640 --> 00:57:53.960
[Guest]: across a grassroot organization who was so steeped into the ideas of liberalism and freedom

00:57:53.960 --> 00:57:57.260
[Guest]: from their experience on the ground.

00:57:57.260 --> 00:58:03.200
[Guest]: That to me was, you know, the next kind of a turning point and that change could happen.

00:58:03.200 --> 00:58:10.400
[Guest]: So that was in the, you know, from the late 90s to early 2000s or mid-2000s or late 2000s.

00:58:10.400 --> 00:58:11.720
[Guest]: So that's probably 10 years.

00:58:11.720 --> 00:58:20.480
[Guest]: It took me to realize that what I am seeing is not an exception, but could be the rule,

00:58:20.480 --> 00:58:26.780
[Guest]: you know, that we could reach out, that it is possible to reach out.

00:58:26.780 --> 00:58:33.600
[Guest]: So what Sharad Joshi showed in actual performance of reaching out, here were people who were

00:58:33.600 --> 00:58:38.920
[Guest]: on the ground, who could still relate their ideals and the people, you know, the ideals

00:58:38.920 --> 00:58:44.660
[Guest]: of freedom and liberalism, etc., with the people and build from that.

00:58:44.660 --> 00:58:51.720
[Guest]: Because most of, a lot of activism still, and more so then, were completely on the other

00:58:51.720 --> 00:58:58.000
[Guest]: side, that we wanted the state to intervene to do this, that and the other, that we accepted

00:58:58.000 --> 00:59:05.000
[Guest]: that people were helpless, ignorant, illiterate and all the troubles that they have, that

00:59:05.000 --> 00:59:09.900
[Guest]: it's the responsibility of the society and the state to do something, to intervene as

00:59:09.900 --> 00:59:14.720
[Guest]: aggressively as they can to root out some of these challenges.

00:59:14.720 --> 00:59:18.360
[Guest]: And here was something that was arguing very differently.

00:59:18.360 --> 00:59:25.200
[Guest]: And in that, another landmark was, and again, primarily because I probably would never have

00:59:25.200 --> 00:59:29.600
[Guest]: observed it or had the opportunity to observe it in such close quarters, had I not come

00:59:29.600 --> 00:59:31.520
[Guest]: to know Archwayane.

00:59:31.520 --> 00:59:40.200
[Guest]: Because they were deeply involved in the forest rights movement for the tribal people for

00:59:40.200 --> 00:59:42.680
[Guest]: a long time.

00:59:42.680 --> 00:59:50.120
[Guest]: And then they were part of the groups that were mobilizing, campaigning for recognition

00:59:50.120 --> 00:59:53.800
[Guest]: of the rights of the tribal people over their lands and local resources in the forest areas

00:59:53.800 --> 00:59:56.000
[Guest]: where they live.

00:59:56.000 --> 01:00:00.360
[Guest]: So that was taking place through the early 2000s.

01:00:00.360 --> 01:00:07.040
[Guest]: And that was another policy change that I saw, not as directly, but through my personal

01:00:07.040 --> 01:00:12.960
[Guest]: interaction with them primarily, that the government did change the policy.

01:00:12.960 --> 01:00:21.560
[Guest]: They did pass an act in 2005, recognizing the rights of the tribal and indigenous communities

01:00:21.560 --> 01:00:27.320
[Guest]: and others who live in conventional, traditional communities who are living in the forest areas,

01:00:27.320 --> 01:00:33.760
[Guest]: whose rights are generally were not recognized till then, so that it was possible.

01:00:33.760 --> 01:00:45.480
[Guest]: And the second learning was that legislative change would never be perfect.

01:00:45.480 --> 01:00:47.840
[Guest]: It will only be incremental.

01:00:47.840 --> 01:00:52.000
[Guest]: And we have to build from that again.

01:00:52.000 --> 01:00:58.320
[Guest]: And it's because many times it happens that we think of a legislative victory and think

01:00:58.320 --> 01:01:01.560
[Guest]: that the battle has been won forever.

01:01:01.560 --> 01:01:06.120
[Guest]: No battles won forever, neither in GM cotton, which is a glaring example that we haven't

01:01:06.120 --> 01:01:13.680
[Guest]: approved the third generation GM cotton since 2006 or 2008.

01:01:13.680 --> 01:01:17.840
[Guest]: The world has moved on to the fifth, sixth, seventh generation of GM.

01:01:17.840 --> 01:01:21.720
[Guest]: And not just in cotton, there are more than 12 GM crops that are being commercially grown

01:01:21.720 --> 01:01:22.720
[Guest]: across the world.

01:01:22.720 --> 01:01:28.640
[Guest]: But we are still debating and stuck with the second generation BT cotton that we had.

01:01:28.640 --> 01:01:32.080
[Guest]: So the battle is never won.

01:01:32.080 --> 01:01:35.840
[Guest]: The battle may be won at a particular point, but the war is a continuous one.

01:01:35.840 --> 01:01:39.960
[Guest]: You have to keep fighting all the time.

01:01:39.960 --> 01:01:41.200
[Guest]: And same with the Forest Rights Act.

01:01:41.200 --> 01:01:44.320
[Guest]: Here was a change, which is a big victory for the people who fought for it.

01:01:44.320 --> 01:01:49.720
[Guest]: I was more marginal in this, but I tried to understand it as closely as I could.

01:01:49.720 --> 01:01:55.000
[Guest]: Because to me, what was interesting and to my friends in ARCH, that it was also a property

01:01:55.000 --> 01:02:01.280
[Guest]: rights movement, which was one of the core beliefs or principles we held of a liberal

01:02:01.280 --> 01:02:07.200
[Guest]: free world, that property in land and whatever else.

01:02:07.200 --> 01:02:15.280
[Guest]: So it's not a perfect legislation, but it's still a step ahead of where we were.

01:02:15.280 --> 01:02:21.280
[Guest]: And again, because of the people, you know, so things perhaps began to fall into place

01:02:21.280 --> 01:02:27.960
[Guest]: that I really need to grapple with this people question even more.

01:02:27.960 --> 01:02:34.760
[Guest]: And then, of course, I had some opportunity to be with them and see how their work were

01:02:34.760 --> 01:02:40.120
[Guest]: actually progressing on the ground and what were the potential and what were the limitations

01:02:40.120 --> 01:02:47.280
[Guest]: as well of reaching out, you know, how it can happen, whether the new communication

01:02:47.280 --> 01:02:53.200
[Guest]: and other technologies available can help, which it did 10 years later with them in terms

01:02:53.200 --> 01:02:59.240
[Guest]: of using satellite imageries and GPS to help people document their claims much, much better

01:02:59.240 --> 01:03:04.120
[Guest]: than it was ever possible when the law was enacted in 2005.

01:03:04.120 --> 01:03:10.280
[Guest]: And people are incrementally getting at least some rights recognized, although perhaps it's

01:03:10.280 --> 01:03:11.280
[Guest]: far from satisfactory.

01:03:11.280 --> 01:03:16.000
[Guest]: There are probably more people whose rights have not been recognized even 10 years or

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:18.640
[Guest]: 15 years after the law was passed then.

01:03:18.640 --> 01:03:20.960
[Guest]: But like I said, it's a continuous journey.

01:03:20.960 --> 01:03:26.560
[Guest]: Every generation, every community has to, every individual has to engage and fight for

01:03:26.560 --> 01:03:29.480
[Guest]: what they stand for.

01:03:29.480 --> 01:03:36.560
[Guest]: So that was, you know, that was the beginning of my trying to really move and try to understand

01:03:36.560 --> 01:03:41.960
[Guest]: that I had missed something, that the people dimension.

01:03:41.960 --> 01:03:51.040
[Guest]: So that probably has been the last 5-7 years and in fact, I just wrote to somebody that

01:03:51.040 --> 01:03:53.240
[Guest]: the people dimension is a practitioner's issue.

01:03:53.240 --> 01:03:54.760
[Guest]: Sharath Joshi was a practitioner.

01:03:54.760 --> 01:03:55.760
[Guest]: He was not an ideologue.

01:03:55.760 --> 01:03:58.680
[Guest]: You know, he was not an armchair ideologue.

01:03:58.680 --> 01:04:00.240
[Guest]: I was an armchair ideologue.

01:04:00.240 --> 01:04:07.120
[Guest]: I could write anything I wanted, anything my imagination would let me and be satisfied

01:04:07.120 --> 01:04:09.760
[Guest]: with it.

01:04:09.760 --> 01:04:17.920
[Guest]: But to implement, and that is where my engineering also fit in, that to implement we need practitioners.

01:04:17.920 --> 01:04:18.920
[Guest]: Engineers are practitioners.

01:04:18.920 --> 01:04:22.380
[Guest]: They are not theoretical physicists.

01:04:22.380 --> 01:04:28.560
[Guest]: And Sharath Joshi was the first practitioner that I saw who made a difference.

01:04:28.560 --> 01:04:36.320
[Guest]: Arch Vaini was another set of practitioners from rural India who had amazing achievements,

01:04:36.320 --> 01:04:38.440
[Guest]: I think.

01:04:38.440 --> 01:04:46.560
[Guest]: And as I looked into it, I rediscovered Gandhi, that here to me is the ideal practitioner.

01:04:46.560 --> 01:04:50.520
[Guest]: Yeah, so it's been a long journey.

01:04:50.520 --> 01:04:57.400
[Guest]: It's been a long journey, but I mean, to me, I mean, it's been a very exciting, exciting

01:04:57.400 --> 01:04:58.400
[Guest]: journey.

01:04:58.400 --> 01:05:02.880
[Guest]: Each breakthrough is, you know, to me, since I'm a non-believer, I don't go to temples

01:05:02.880 --> 01:05:04.960
[Guest]: or have any prayer to say.

01:05:04.960 --> 01:05:13.480
[Guest]: To me, these are as ecstatic or as I could, I could enjoy it as much as any other excitement

01:05:13.480 --> 01:05:16.960
[Guest]: stimulus I could have, so.

01:05:16.960 --> 01:05:19.240
[Amit Varma]: So we'll discuss Gandhi in length later.

01:05:19.240 --> 01:05:22.760
[Amit Varma]: And I'll also double click on the Arch Vaini forest rights movements, because I think there

01:05:22.760 --> 01:05:25.160
[Amit Varma]: are so many lessons there.

01:05:25.160 --> 01:05:30.520
[Amit Varma]: So before we do that, an observation, a little setting of context, another observation, and

01:05:30.520 --> 01:05:33.280
[Amit Varma]: then a couple of questions in that order.

01:05:33.280 --> 01:05:37.480
[Amit Varma]: So my first observation is that, you know, I used to believe that many of the things

01:05:37.480 --> 01:05:43.160
[Amit Varma]: we believe in are counterintuitive ideas, like the fact that every voluntary interaction

01:05:43.160 --> 01:05:46.360
[Amit Varma]: between two people is a positive sum game, both people are better off, what I call the

01:05:46.360 --> 01:05:51.600
[Amit Varma]: double thank you moment, or spontaneous order, the way it works, that you don't need something

01:05:51.600 --> 01:05:57.760
[Amit Varma]: to be centrally directed, that societies and languages and cultures, you know, should not

01:05:57.760 --> 01:06:00.160
[Amit Varma]: be centrally directed, they can run on their own.

01:06:00.160 --> 01:06:05.560
[Amit Varma]: And I thought these are counterintuitive ideas, and people may not necessarily understand.

01:06:05.560 --> 01:06:10.760
[Amit Varma]: And one experience which forced me to reconsider this notion of mine, was when you called me

01:06:10.760 --> 01:06:15.840
[Amit Varma]: to that farmers conference in Deolali three years ago, where in fact, I had had that conversation

01:06:15.840 --> 01:06:18.560
[Amit Varma]: with Gunawan Patilji episode 86.

01:06:18.560 --> 01:06:24.680
[Amit Varma]: And there I realized that all of these people, farmers and farmer leaders held pretty much

01:06:24.680 --> 01:06:29.520
[Amit Varma]: identical ideas to mine, except that those ideas did not come from books and thinking,

01:06:29.520 --> 01:06:31.680
[Amit Varma]: they came from lived experience.

01:06:31.680 --> 01:06:34.940
[Amit Varma]: And that these weren't necessarily that counterintuitive.

01:06:34.940 --> 01:06:41.000
[Amit Varma]: It was from the fabric of their lives, they could devise these lessons, they could protest

01:06:41.000 --> 01:06:46.480
[Amit Varma]: against the oppression of the state, and realize all the ways in which they were sort of held

01:06:46.480 --> 01:06:47.480
[Amit Varma]: back.

01:06:47.480 --> 01:06:52.400
[Amit Varma]: So that was a moment for me, which taught me that don't be condescending, don't be patronizing

01:06:52.400 --> 01:06:57.880
[Amit Varma]: these people, you know, from their lived experience, they can arrive at, you know, similar ideas

01:06:57.880 --> 01:07:02.320
[Amit Varma]: to you, except that they are in a sense deeper, because it's come from the bottom up.

01:07:02.320 --> 01:07:04.760
[Amit Varma]: And it's not like a top down intellectual thing.

01:07:04.760 --> 01:07:10.040
[Amit Varma]: The context I want to set is I want to click a little bit on the Julian Simon and the population

01:07:10.040 --> 01:07:14.960
[Amit Varma]: thing, that this is a common trend through Indian history and a dangerous trend, which

01:07:14.960 --> 01:07:18.640
[Amit Varma]: is why I want to click on it, that we assume that our population is the greatest of our

01:07:18.640 --> 01:07:20.160
[Amit Varma]: problems.

01:07:20.160 --> 01:07:25.560
[Amit Varma]: And this is also a belief that's been incentivized by others, for example, in the early 50s,

01:07:25.560 --> 01:07:30.000
[Amit Varma]: I think the Ford Foundation in the late 50s and early 60s, rather, the Ford Foundation

01:07:30.000 --> 01:07:33.480
[Amit Varma]: was giving incentives to India to do population control.

01:07:33.480 --> 01:07:37.640
[Amit Varma]: Population control was a big theme, Sanjay Gandhi kind of believed in it and did a lot

01:07:37.640 --> 01:07:42.160
[Amit Varma]: of coercive nonsense, Kumi Kapoor has a great book on the emergency, which talks about that

01:07:42.160 --> 01:07:44.240
[Amit Varma]: absolute monster.

01:07:44.240 --> 01:07:48.760
[Amit Varma]: And this belief has kind of persisted to the current day, where there are still incentives

01:07:48.760 --> 01:07:51.600
[Amit Varma]: given for Nazbandis and population control and all of that.

01:07:51.600 --> 01:07:55.440
[Amit Varma]: And at the time we are recording in November, there have been rumors for a while that this

01:07:55.440 --> 01:07:57.920
[Amit Varma]: government may do some population control policy.

01:07:57.920 --> 01:08:02.320
[Amit Varma]: But the truth is, population is not a problem.

01:08:02.320 --> 01:08:06.120
[Amit Varma]: Population is, in the words of Julian Simon, he wrote a book with this title, the ultimate

01:08:06.120 --> 01:08:07.800
[Amit Varma]: resource.

01:08:07.800 --> 01:08:10.260
[Amit Varma]: People are brains, not stomachs.

01:08:10.260 --> 01:08:11.620
[Amit Varma]: This is fundamental.

01:08:11.620 --> 01:08:17.640
[Amit Varma]: And one thing that illustrates this is that the movement of human beings throughout history

01:08:17.640 --> 01:08:23.760
[Amit Varma]: has been a movement from villages and rural areas to cities and urban areas to places

01:08:23.760 --> 01:08:28.280
[Amit Varma]: with more population density, because that population density is a feature, not a bug.

01:08:28.280 --> 01:08:31.960
[Amit Varma]: You have deeper economic networks, more opportunities, all of that.

01:08:31.960 --> 01:08:32.960
[Amit Varma]: That's why people go to cities.

01:08:32.960 --> 01:08:38.780
[Amit Varma]: There's a great study by Nicholas Eberstadt in 2007 called Too Many People?

01:08:38.780 --> 01:08:42.380
[Amit Varma]: And that found no correlation between population density and poverty.

01:08:42.380 --> 01:08:47.640
[Amit Varma]: You know, Monaco has 40 times the population density of Bangladesh, Bahrain has three times

01:08:47.640 --> 01:08:49.940
[Amit Varma]: the population density of India.

01:08:49.940 --> 01:08:54.940
[Amit Varma]: So this is a terrible misconception and it's important to point that out because it leads

01:08:54.940 --> 01:09:02.680
[Amit Varma]: to coercive policies on common people, which are crimes on humanity and this kind of thinking

01:09:02.680 --> 01:09:03.680
[Amit Varma]: still continues.

01:09:03.680 --> 01:09:06.120
[Amit Varma]: So I'm really glad that you kind of mentioned that.

01:09:06.120 --> 01:09:07.120
[Amit Varma]: And it's very interesting.

01:09:07.120 --> 01:09:10.280
[Amit Varma]: I never knew you'd corresponded extensively with Simon.

01:09:10.280 --> 01:09:14.640
[Amit Varma]: The other sort of sideways observation I'll come to is Ayn Rand.

01:09:14.640 --> 01:09:18.760
[Amit Varma]: In the sense it's become fashionable, for example, on Twitter, too shit on Ayn Rand.

01:09:18.760 --> 01:09:23.480
[Amit Varma]: I got to say, I haven't read Rand, I tried and I didn't like the quality of the prose

01:09:23.480 --> 01:09:25.480
[Amit Varma]: and just for that reason alone, I didn't.

01:09:25.480 --> 01:09:29.360
[Amit Varma]: I've seen some of her quotes, which sound very interesting to me and I agree with them.

01:09:29.360 --> 01:09:35.680
[Amit Varma]: For example, the smallest minority is an individual, which I think is something we should all internalize.

01:09:35.680 --> 01:09:38.480
[Amit Varma]: But it's kind of become fashionable to have this thing about what is the worst book ever

01:09:38.480 --> 01:09:41.000
[Amit Varma]: and people will say Fountainhead or Atlas Shrugged.

01:09:41.000 --> 01:09:47.600
[Amit Varma]: And it's such a, you know, this speaks to a tendency within us to show our virtue by

01:09:47.600 --> 01:09:51.280
[Amit Varma]: standing in judgment over others, like I am too good for that.

01:09:51.280 --> 01:09:52.280
[Amit Varma]: That is so bad.

01:09:52.280 --> 01:09:55.240
[Amit Varma]: See, I am so discerning, I know that is bad.

01:09:55.240 --> 01:10:00.360
[Amit Varma]: And to me, that question itself, what is the worst book ever, is fundamentally flawed.

01:10:00.360 --> 01:10:04.240
[Amit Varma]: Because you know, whenever any of us starts reading a really bad book, we stop reading

01:10:04.240 --> 01:10:07.280
[Amit Varma]: if we never read it, we don't complete bad books.

01:10:07.280 --> 01:10:10.720
[Amit Varma]: So how are we in a position to judge what is the worst book ever?

01:10:10.720 --> 01:10:15.200
[Amit Varma]: We simply are not and I bet that many of the people who write these things haven't read

01:10:15.200 --> 01:10:16.800
[Amit Varma]: Rand and neither have I.

01:10:16.800 --> 01:10:21.120
[Amit Varma]: And I know that we share many of the same beliefs about individual freedom and liberty

01:10:21.120 --> 01:10:23.680
[Amit Varma]: and why consent is good and coercion is bad.

01:10:23.680 --> 01:10:26.200
[Amit Varma]: And I have arrived at it through different places.

01:10:26.200 --> 01:10:31.400
[Amit Varma]: And to some extent you and another person I also admire greatly, who's influenced by

01:10:31.400 --> 01:10:35.800
[Amit Varma]: Rand, which is Alex Tabarrok, both of you have arrived at it through Rand.

01:10:35.800 --> 01:10:41.960
[Amit Varma]: So I'd like you to kind of talk about the ideas that like, how does she change your

01:10:41.960 --> 01:10:42.960
[Amit Varma]: thinking?

01:10:42.960 --> 01:10:43.960
[Amit Varma]: What are the ideas?

01:10:43.960 --> 01:10:47.240
[Amit Varma]: What are your thoughts of looking at the world that you got from Anne Rand?

01:10:47.240 --> 01:10:53.600
[Guest]: You know, Rand was a, was kind of a shock.

01:10:53.600 --> 01:11:02.680
[Guest]: That from everything that I had heard, read, experienced in the first 25 years, and I read

01:11:02.680 --> 01:11:07.240
[Guest]: Rand relatively late in my life, I was already a graduate and all that.

01:11:07.240 --> 01:11:11.480
[Guest]: Most people read Rand, begin to read Rand, it seems, in their school or high school or

01:11:11.480 --> 01:11:12.480
[Guest]: college.

01:11:12.480 --> 01:11:16.640
[Guest]: So I read Rand late and perhaps because we didn't have, there was no internet and there

01:11:16.640 --> 01:11:22.720
[Guest]: was no such thing to get to acquaint with her and I read her by accident.

01:11:22.720 --> 01:11:33.200
[Guest]: But the shock of it, that how could somebody think and provide a perspective which seems

01:11:33.200 --> 01:11:46.200
[Guest]: to stand against or stand alone in the backdrop of everything we have read, heard, believed.

01:11:46.200 --> 01:11:51.840
[Guest]: And what you said that, you know, and that the individual is the smallest minority in

01:11:51.840 --> 01:11:57.720
[Guest]: any collective, no matter which group, whereas today we talk of all the minorities, minority

01:11:57.720 --> 01:12:03.440
[Guest]: rights, etc., but we never consider the individual within those minorities.

01:12:03.440 --> 01:12:07.240
[Guest]: Because that's the unifying bond, that could be the potentially unifying bond cutting across

01:12:07.240 --> 01:12:12.840
[Guest]: various communities, ideological, ethnic, religious.

01:12:12.840 --> 01:12:19.560
[Guest]: And second was that, and because perhaps, and this is perhaps my context, because I

01:12:19.560 --> 01:12:25.120
[Guest]: came from engineering, I studied science, pure science, physics, chemistry, mathematics

01:12:25.120 --> 01:12:26.880
[Guest]: throughout my education.

01:12:26.880 --> 01:12:34.040
[Guest]: So I had no particular inclination or understanding of social sciences at all.

01:12:34.040 --> 01:12:40.480
[Guest]: And that Rand could provide, and perhaps because I was a blank slate, Rand, at least in that

01:12:40.480 --> 01:12:47.760
[Guest]: dimension, so Rand could provide a social science explanation for what's happening

01:12:47.760 --> 01:12:49.880
[Guest]: in such a telling manner.

01:12:49.880 --> 01:12:55.320
[Guest]: And which is probably why I think people, the books are pirated and I first, in fact

01:12:55.320 --> 01:13:02.400
[Guest]: long before I even realized what intellectual property and copyright, etc., were, I used

01:13:02.400 --> 01:13:08.080
[Guest]: to buy, and I still have some of those copies, bought copies from the streets of Calcutta

01:13:08.080 --> 01:13:12.400
[Guest]: which were all, from today I know, they were all pirated.

01:13:12.400 --> 01:13:18.720
[Guest]: You know, if people were not reading, no one would be pirating and copying and printing

01:13:18.720 --> 01:13:19.720
[Guest]: them.

01:13:19.720 --> 01:13:22.000
[Guest]: And in those days, even photocopying was so difficult.

01:13:22.000 --> 01:13:26.680
[Guest]: Yeah, photocopying was not as easy as it is today.

01:13:26.680 --> 01:13:33.040
[Guest]: So all that, and which meant that in Calcutta I did, when I began to read, I began to really

01:13:33.040 --> 01:13:34.040
[Guest]: read.

01:13:34.040 --> 01:13:37.440
[Guest]: One, because reading came naturally to me, and secondly, I could look around and I could

01:13:37.440 --> 01:13:42.280
[Guest]: find so many of her books and the books that she recommended and otherwise.

01:13:42.280 --> 01:13:50.120
[Guest]: So that was, and my first impulse, in fact, not just me, another friend whom both of us

01:13:50.120 --> 01:13:59.080
[Guest]: know, Parth, we came across each other in, around that time, 86 perhaps, because of our

01:13:59.080 --> 01:14:03.160
[Guest]: common affinity to Rand.

01:14:03.160 --> 01:14:11.520
[Guest]: And some others also, Rakesh Wadhwa, another friend you know, Ajay Gandhi, another friend

01:14:11.520 --> 01:14:12.520
[Unknown]: you know.

01:14:12.520 --> 01:14:13.520
[Unknown]: Wonderful man, so sad.

01:14:13.520 --> 01:14:17.240
[Guest]: Yeah, we all, we all, so sad that he passed away so suddenly last month, amazing, I still

01:14:17.240 --> 01:14:23.680
[Guest]: miss him each day, because he used to correspond so much on WhatsApp, almost on a daily basis.

01:14:23.680 --> 01:14:30.440
[Guest]: So all these people I came to know, and many others, and most prominent of them, my wife.

01:14:30.440 --> 01:14:36.280
[Guest]: That it's in the 80s, late 80s that we had these Aindran clubs in many parts of, many

01:14:36.280 --> 01:14:37.280
[Guest]: cities of India.

01:14:37.280 --> 01:14:42.480
[Guest]: And we used to circulate reading material and audio cassettes to listen to, because

01:14:42.480 --> 01:14:45.680
[Guest]: you know, we had to literally post them from one place to another.

01:14:45.680 --> 01:14:49.640
[Guest]: One group would listen to first few sets and pass the rest of the lectures to the next

01:14:49.640 --> 01:14:50.640
[Guest]: group, etc.

01:14:50.640 --> 01:14:54.720
[Guest]: So it was a large network, which is how I came to know some of these people in Tara

01:14:54.720 --> 01:14:57.920
[Guest]: Malkani and Govind Malkani in Bombay.

01:14:57.920 --> 01:15:03.440
[Guest]: So in that, in the personal journey, that period was interesting, because we were all

01:15:03.440 --> 01:15:07.320
[Guest]: exploring to figure out, are there other people like us?

01:15:07.320 --> 01:15:09.280
[Guest]: Or are we being taken for a ride?

01:15:09.280 --> 01:15:13.720
[Guest]: You know, so it was amazing to discover Parth or so many others.

01:15:13.720 --> 01:15:17.880
[Guest]: And that's how I met my wife, because she responded to one of these efforts.

01:15:17.880 --> 01:15:27.240
[Guest]: And because she was in, she was from Calcutta, so we could meet up in 87, 88 perhaps, and

01:15:27.240 --> 01:15:28.960
[Guest]: we married in 89.

01:15:28.960 --> 01:15:38.400
[Guest]: And that's one person probably, I mean, I have no, I can't express how, how glad I am

01:15:38.400 --> 01:15:39.400
[Guest]: for that coincidence.

01:15:39.400 --> 01:15:41.080
[Guest]: Love at first sight.

01:15:41.080 --> 01:15:46.240
[Guest]: Yeah, it was, it was, but more than that, she, I mean, much more than that, because

01:15:46.240 --> 01:15:49.200
[Guest]: she's borne me for the last 30 years.

01:15:49.200 --> 01:15:54.880
[Guest]: Yeah, it's not easy, because of my habits and because of my way of doing things, that

01:15:54.880 --> 01:16:00.120
[Guest]: she's virtually subsidized a lot of what I do and what I think.

01:16:00.120 --> 01:16:06.580
[Guest]: So that's been, on a personal level, an incredible, incredible journey.

01:16:06.580 --> 01:16:13.280
[Guest]: And that we shared so much in common, at least, you know, the basic premises.

01:16:13.280 --> 01:16:20.680
[Guest]: So that was, yeah, that was, RAND was in that sense, quite, I mean, quite startling.

01:16:20.680 --> 01:16:23.520
[Guest]: Because I had, perhaps because I had not come from that world.

01:16:23.520 --> 01:16:27.760
[Guest]: Maybe people from the social sciences who are already familiar with economics and social

01:16:27.760 --> 01:16:35.040
[Guest]: issues, they have a frame and therefore can assess and therefore can reject RAND as much.

01:16:35.040 --> 01:16:40.960
[Guest]: But I think most people do not, like me, so many people like me then, do not come from

01:16:40.960 --> 01:16:45.040
[Guest]: a set perspective, because for any number of reasons, either we didn't, we're not educated

01:16:45.040 --> 01:16:48.760
[Guest]: in that stream, or we are not practitioners in that stream.

01:16:48.760 --> 01:16:53.720
[Guest]: You know, so that probably, and which is probably why people like RAND sell across the world

01:16:53.720 --> 01:16:58.000
[Guest]: or continue to sell, how many years, 30 years after her death.

01:16:58.000 --> 01:17:01.560
[Guest]: In 82 she died and the books are still being pirated.

01:17:01.560 --> 01:17:07.520
[Guest]: I mean, this is a phenomenon I cannot, you know, one can't understand unless one feels

01:17:07.520 --> 01:17:13.400
[Guest]: that there are people who are, of course, reading doesn't make one take it up in any

01:17:13.400 --> 01:17:14.400
[Guest]: meaningful manner.

01:17:14.400 --> 01:17:20.480
[Guest]: But to me, I mean, I probably took it up a little bit more than some others.

01:17:20.480 --> 01:17:27.360
[Guest]: But that was, to me, that was my first and the Julian Simon was my next.

01:17:27.360 --> 01:17:35.480
[Guest]: And one query, I mean, of course, RAND made me completely convinced me about the needlessness

01:17:35.480 --> 01:17:42.280
[Guest]: of believing in God or a superhuman force or person or whatever.

01:17:42.280 --> 01:17:49.120
[Guest]: So she completely cured me of that.

01:17:49.120 --> 01:17:57.480
[Guest]: But what she didn't show, which kind of came to me much, much later, 20-25 years later

01:17:57.480 --> 01:18:04.120
[Guest]: is, and what I said a little earlier, that the point is not about winning the debate,

01:18:04.120 --> 01:18:06.360
[Guest]: the point is about winning over.

01:18:06.360 --> 01:18:14.120
[Guest]: Sharad Joshi gave a glimpse of that winning over, Arch Vaini provided another glimpse

01:18:14.120 --> 01:18:20.160
[Guest]: of trying to reach out and winning over people who may not be coming from your side.

01:18:20.160 --> 01:18:25.480
[Guest]: And the ultimate one, for instance, for me is in this regard of winning over and not

01:18:25.480 --> 01:18:28.840
[Guest]: being a practitioner to the core, to me is Gandhi.

01:18:28.840 --> 01:18:33.960
[Guest]: Because public policy, and which again is my, you know, I mean, my re-reading of Gandhi,

01:18:33.960 --> 01:18:38.440
[Guest]: that public policy, if you have to take people forward with you on the on issues that you

01:18:38.440 --> 01:18:48.760
[Guest]: think deserve social, political capital to back it, then no one, I think, in the modern

01:18:48.760 --> 01:18:59.720
[Guest]: era or perhaps ever, could reach out and connect at a scale and at a time that Gandhi did.

01:18:59.720 --> 01:19:06.320
[Guest]: So that to me was, you know, so to me, in fact, this is my current, my latest passion,

01:19:06.320 --> 01:19:13.760
[Guest]: that if I really believe that it is not about winning the debate, but winning over people

01:19:13.760 --> 01:19:23.960
[Guest]: with whom I may disagree, it is not so much to convince them of my merits, but about legitimacy

01:19:23.960 --> 01:19:30.280
[Guest]: of the different perspectives, because once we recognise the legitimacy of different perspectives,

01:19:30.280 --> 01:19:35.280
[Guest]: then we will take a step back from imposing our perspective on others.

01:19:35.280 --> 01:19:40.760
[Guest]: So that's the first step, and in that, I think, my current, this thing has been, I mean, I'm

01:19:40.760 --> 01:19:45.600
[Guest]: completely into it, personally, as well as intellectually.

01:19:45.600 --> 01:19:54.520
[Guest]: How do I reconcile, for instance, Rand with Gandhi?

01:19:54.520 --> 01:20:00.660
[Guest]: You know, there would seem, until 10 years ago, I would have thought that it's not easy.

01:20:00.660 --> 01:20:06.920
[Guest]: But precisely because it didn't seem easy, I'm now completely into it.

01:20:06.920 --> 01:20:09.280
[Guest]: That if it's not easy, is there a way?

01:20:09.280 --> 01:20:14.640
[Guest]: That how do we reconcile people and ideas that I think, and that many of us think, are

01:20:14.640 --> 01:20:15.640
[Guest]: irreconcilable?

01:20:15.640 --> 01:20:27.160
[Guest]: Is there something in the ideal, in the premises of socialism, which can be brought together

01:20:27.160 --> 01:20:35.600
[Guest]: with the premises of a free society, for instance, or if there is Julian Simon's way of looking

01:20:35.600 --> 01:20:39.160
[Guest]: at environment and consumption, etc.

01:20:39.160 --> 01:20:43.960
[Guest]: That mind is the ultimate resource, and therefore, the more we consume, the more we have.

01:20:43.960 --> 01:20:49.240
[Guest]: And which, to me, was one of my direct experiences, that when I spent a few years in the villages

01:20:49.240 --> 01:20:53.800
[Guest]: of Sundarbans, we consumed hardly anything.

01:20:53.800 --> 01:20:56.520
[Guest]: But we didn't even have tap water.

01:20:56.520 --> 01:20:59.360
[Guest]: I mean, we had to really struggle to get clean water.

01:20:59.360 --> 01:21:00.360
[Guest]: And we had no toilets.

01:21:00.360 --> 01:21:03.760
[Guest]: So it was all outdoors.

01:21:03.760 --> 01:21:05.440
[Guest]: And we had no consumption.

01:21:05.440 --> 01:21:12.920
[Guest]: Yet when I saw the West, they were consuming so much, but it was so clean.

01:21:12.920 --> 01:21:18.400
[Guest]: You know, so to me, it's not necessary that consumption leads to pollution, or there is

01:21:18.400 --> 01:21:20.720
[Guest]: something called overconsumption leading to pollution.

01:21:20.720 --> 01:21:24.440
[Guest]: So how do I reconcile Julian Simon with, again, Gandhi?

01:21:24.440 --> 01:21:29.720
[Guest]: Because Gandhi would be seen as, you know, the famous quote, which is kind of tenuous,

01:21:29.720 --> 01:21:33.400
[Guest]: but still, I mean, which is referred to, although he may not have actually said it, that the

01:21:33.400 --> 01:21:38.320
[Guest]: world is enough for everyone's need, but not sufficient for everyone's greed.

01:21:38.320 --> 01:21:44.200
[Guest]: Because then we don't, I mean, no one goes on to define what's need and what's greed

01:21:44.200 --> 01:21:45.200
[Guest]: is.

01:21:45.200 --> 01:21:47.880
[Guest]: And Gandhi was not an intellectual, he was not in the business of defining things in

01:21:47.880 --> 01:21:48.880
[Guest]: that manner.

01:21:48.880 --> 01:21:49.880
[Guest]: He was a practitioner.

01:21:49.880 --> 01:21:52.400
[Guest]: We had to see it from his life.

01:21:52.400 --> 01:21:56.640
[Amit Varma]: So some trends, one, I think that there might be a false dichotomy here, in the sense, I

01:21:56.640 --> 01:22:01.400
[Amit Varma]: think it is possible to be like you probably are both a Randian and a Gandhian, in the

01:22:01.400 --> 01:22:07.400
[Amit Varma]: sense that if you look at Rand in say, the business of ideas, that this is the way the

01:22:07.400 --> 01:22:08.400
[Amit Varma]: world works.

01:22:08.400 --> 01:22:12.960
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, these are values which help move us to a better place, then that's a business

01:22:12.960 --> 01:22:14.000
[Amit Varma]: of ideas.

01:22:14.000 --> 01:22:18.320
[Amit Varma]: And Gandhi more in the business of that second aspect that you spoke about, how do you convince

01:22:18.320 --> 01:22:19.320
[Amit Varma]: people?

01:22:19.320 --> 01:22:20.320
[Amit Varma]: How do you bring people with you?

01:22:20.320 --> 01:22:22.520
[Amit Varma]: How do you build mass movements, all of that.

01:22:22.520 --> 01:22:26.840
[Amit Varma]: And I think that they're kind of orthogonal and can, you know, one can follow the other

01:22:26.840 --> 01:22:32.480
[Amit Varma]: one can learn from Gandhi, how to build a movement, but not necessarily share many of

01:22:32.480 --> 01:22:33.480
[Amit Varma]: his ideas.

01:22:33.480 --> 01:22:38.840
[Amit Varma]: And as you know, I admire many of his ideas, I despise many of his ideas.

01:22:38.840 --> 01:22:42.280
[Amit Varma]: People contain multitudes, there are all of those kind of angles.

01:22:42.280 --> 01:22:46.040
[Amit Varma]: I want to now double click on again, something that you alluded to earlier and to just now

01:22:46.040 --> 01:22:52.400
[Amit Varma]: where you said that once you sort of found this frame of looking at the world from Rand,

01:22:52.400 --> 01:22:57.720
[Amit Varma]: from Simon and so on, you moved heavily into the environment, which I find really interesting,

01:22:57.720 --> 01:23:01.760
[Amit Varma]: because, you know, people who support the free markets like you and me, talk about the

01:23:01.760 --> 01:23:02.760
[Amit Varma]: beauty of markets.

01:23:02.760 --> 01:23:08.360
[Amit Varma]: The most common counter given to them always is that, okay, fine, we accept that all voluntary

01:23:08.360 --> 01:23:12.280
[Amit Varma]: transactions leave both people better off and markets are great and blah, blah, blah.

01:23:12.280 --> 01:23:16.720
[Amit Varma]: But what about externalities, what about the environment, what about pollution?

01:23:16.720 --> 01:23:18.080
[Amit Varma]: What about the smog of Delhi?

01:23:18.080 --> 01:23:20.800
[Amit Varma]: What about, you know, all of those things?

01:23:20.800 --> 01:23:25.520
[Amit Varma]: Take me through sort of your thinking about all these issues, because that also seems

01:23:25.520 --> 01:23:31.400
[Amit Varma]: a very interesting reconciliation to make, to be able to go into that domain like you

01:23:31.400 --> 01:23:37.880
[Amit Varma]: did to, you know, to band with all the experts on it, and the practitioners on it, to enter

01:23:37.880 --> 01:23:44.080
[Amit Varma]: mass movements, all the while, holding firm about how, you know, you need to look at it

01:23:44.080 --> 01:23:47.400
[Amit Varma]: a little differently, that markets aren't evil, maybe they are the solution.

01:23:47.400 --> 01:23:51.760
[Amit Varma]: So expand on that a little bit, because I'm sure many people who have this objection to

01:23:51.760 --> 01:23:54.360
[Amit Varma]: free markets would be interested in knowing.

01:23:54.360 --> 01:23:59.680
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, I was not looking at people at that point, primarily, I was looking at

01:23:59.680 --> 01:24:05.440
[Guest]: it as a challenging intellectual exercise, which was very satisfying, because I was looking

01:24:05.440 --> 01:24:12.000
[Guest]: into a problem differently, and I was applying it to our context in India, rather than what

01:24:12.000 --> 01:24:18.600
[Guest]: one would hear or read from the Western or other context.

01:24:18.600 --> 01:24:25.200
[Guest]: And you know, so for instance, I found it quite natural, which I know is not so natural.

01:24:25.200 --> 01:24:28.640
[Guest]: But I found it natural in those days, one of the first questions that kind of struck

01:24:28.640 --> 01:24:37.080
[Guest]: me is that how come we have more chickens than we have more tigers or elephants.

01:24:37.080 --> 01:24:43.240
[Guest]: And that to me was relevant, because, and from personal experience too, because I grew

01:24:43.240 --> 01:24:48.760
[Guest]: up at a time in the 60s, when there was hardly any chicken, you know, chicken was, I think

01:24:48.760 --> 01:24:54.320
[Guest]: in our house, Bengali household, complete non-vegetarian all the time.

01:24:54.320 --> 01:24:59.040
[Guest]: I think we had chicken only in the 70s, started having chicken only in the 70s, before that

01:24:59.040 --> 01:25:04.120
[Guest]: it was mutton, the goat or at times if there are people coming from the village, it was

01:25:04.120 --> 01:25:08.520
[Guest]: the duck, there was no chicken.

01:25:08.520 --> 01:25:13.200
[Guest]: And my grandmother, as long as she was running the house, she would not let chicken be cooked

01:25:13.200 --> 01:25:21.000
[Guest]: in the common chulha, you know, the coal-fired stove that we had, I mean that everyone had

01:25:21.000 --> 01:25:23.360
[Guest]: at that time.

01:25:23.360 --> 01:25:28.360
[Guest]: So, why is it that we have so many chickens?

01:25:28.360 --> 01:25:34.360
[Guest]: You know, that was kind of a filling, I mean fill in the blank kind that how is it that

01:25:34.360 --> 01:25:44.120
[Guest]: a western city, New York or London or Tokyo, where not just there is huge population, enormous

01:25:44.120 --> 01:25:50.800
[Guest]: wealth and incredibly clean.

01:25:50.800 --> 01:25:57.840
[Guest]: You know, so all the three were together, so that to me was my kind of lived experience

01:25:57.840 --> 01:26:03.240
[Guest]: that there is something that we need to explore, that we need to understand.

01:26:03.240 --> 01:26:09.320
[Guest]: And that is where I think Rand and the Simon and all the rest kind of, Rand for instance,

01:26:09.320 --> 01:26:16.760
[Guest]: the basic advantage was that she provided an ethical frame of the idea of rights and

01:26:16.760 --> 01:26:21.720
[Guest]: what's right and wrong as a first shot, which I hadn't thought of earlier.

01:26:21.720 --> 01:26:30.160
[Guest]: And Julian Simon with his enormous information base on how things are changing, was that

01:26:30.160 --> 01:26:36.480
[Guest]: you know, if this is really happening, then why isn't it happening here?

01:26:36.480 --> 01:26:42.160
[Guest]: You know, and perhaps while India was reforming, liberalizing in 1990s, that was, I mean I

01:26:42.160 --> 01:26:46.840
[Guest]: really didn't have the technical expertise to look into the fiscal policy or, you know,

01:26:46.840 --> 01:26:50.120
[Guest]: things of that kind.

01:26:50.120 --> 01:26:54.360
[Guest]: So my interest grew into environment because, you know, that was a big, you know, 92 was

01:26:54.360 --> 01:26:55.360
[Guest]: the Rio summit.

01:26:55.360 --> 01:26:59.520
[Guest]: So, you know, that was a big buzz and then WTO, so that was another big buzz.

01:26:59.520 --> 01:27:04.240
[Guest]: So I plunged into it because there were big buzzes and because I wanted to know, I really

01:27:04.240 --> 01:27:08.960
[Guest]: wanted to explore that is there something I can say or think which makes sense to me

01:27:08.960 --> 01:27:09.960
[Guest]: firstly.

01:27:09.960 --> 01:27:12.480
[Guest]: And if it makes sense to me, then I can take it forward.

01:27:12.480 --> 01:27:19.920
[Guest]: So the environment fit in exactly in that post-Rio scenario.

01:27:19.920 --> 01:27:23.720
[Guest]: And the more I looked, the more I felt that I can ask questions which people are not asking

01:27:23.720 --> 01:27:24.720
[Guest]: and which needs to be asked.

01:27:24.720 --> 01:27:28.120
[Guest]: For instance, why there are more chicken than tigers and this thing.

01:27:28.120 --> 01:27:34.320
[Guest]: So I, one of my first, and not just chicken, there are more crocodiles, there are probably

01:27:34.320 --> 01:27:40.400
[Guest]: 2 million crocodiles being killed across the world for the leather, whereas in India, crocodile

01:27:40.400 --> 01:27:46.680
[Guest]: is an endangered species and harvesting and farming is illegal, prohibited.

01:27:46.680 --> 01:27:47.680
[Guest]: Why?

01:27:47.680 --> 01:27:55.880
[Guest]: You know, and to me, that was one of my starting this thing and it was at around that time

01:27:55.880 --> 01:28:01.680
[Guest]: probably, I do not remember the exact year now, that I came across, because I was exploring

01:28:01.680 --> 01:28:09.560
[Guest]: these ideas, came across the ideas and experiences of a person, I do not know, I mean which most

01:28:09.560 --> 01:28:14.520
[Guest]: Indians may not remember these days, Romulus Whitaker.

01:28:14.520 --> 01:28:23.360
[Guest]: He, I do not know what his background was, but he set up a farm in outside Chennai, Madras.

01:28:23.360 --> 01:28:27.440
[Guest]: And once, I think my wife and I, we were on that stretch of the East Coast and had visited

01:28:27.440 --> 01:28:30.600
[Guest]: them once.

01:28:30.600 --> 01:28:38.720
[Guest]: The answer, question was, here is a farm that was pioneer in the world in terms of figuring

01:28:38.720 --> 01:28:44.320
[Guest]: out how to ensure a more efficient breeding of crocodiles, but has been prohibited from

01:28:44.320 --> 01:28:48.440
[Guest]: breeding.

01:28:48.440 --> 01:28:57.640
[Guest]: So that to me, perhaps because I was not coming from the stream, I had a frame which was different.

01:28:57.640 --> 01:29:02.000
[Guest]: My experience and the frame, I was trying to link the two, because I had nothing else

01:29:02.000 --> 01:29:03.000
[Guest]: to go by.

01:29:03.000 --> 01:29:06.960
[Guest]: I had no baggage, so to say, to carry.

01:29:06.960 --> 01:29:15.040
[Guest]: So that to me was my, you know, I mean, so when I wrote one of my kind of pieces, which

01:29:15.040 --> 01:29:20.080
[Guest]: a lot of people remember 10-20 years after that, I still remember it, that New York Times

01:29:20.080 --> 01:29:21.080
[Guest]: piece on tigers.

01:29:21.080 --> 01:29:22.080
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah.

01:29:22.080 --> 01:29:23.080
[Guest]: But why could not it be?

01:29:23.080 --> 01:29:24.080
[Guest]: Why can not we think?

01:29:24.080 --> 01:29:27.120
[Amit Varma]: Why can not we imagine a world which is different?

01:29:27.120 --> 01:29:30.920
[Amit Varma]: I'll quickly tell my listeners what that piece was, because I remember reading it and being

01:29:30.920 --> 01:29:32.600
[Amit Varma]: absolutely mind blown.

01:29:32.600 --> 01:29:36.840
[Amit Varma]: And your piece essentially made the argument, and I think it was in the context of China,

01:29:36.840 --> 01:29:42.240
[Amit Varma]: that if you want to save tigers, and you know, make sure that they don't die out, the way

01:29:42.240 --> 01:29:48.280
[Amit Varma]: to do it is to allow commercialization of tigers, because then people will be incentivized

01:29:48.280 --> 01:29:51.960
[Amit Varma]: to breed tigers, and therefore the species won't die out exactly as has happened with

01:29:51.960 --> 01:29:55.240
[Amit Varma]: chickens and crocodiles elsewhere in the world, but not here.

01:29:55.240 --> 01:29:59.000
[Amit Varma]: And that is so counterintuitive, because your intuitive response when you think about how

01:29:59.000 --> 01:30:02.520
[Amit Varma]: do I endanger a species is stop people from killing it.

01:30:02.520 --> 01:30:06.520
[Amit Varma]: But your answer is do the opposite, and they will thrive and you know, the difference between

01:30:06.520 --> 01:30:07.520
[Amit Varma]: chicken and tigers.

01:30:07.520 --> 01:30:08.520
[Guest]: So sorry, continue.

01:30:08.520 --> 01:30:09.520
[Guest]: But I just had to share.

01:30:09.520 --> 01:30:10.520
[Guest]: Yeah, exactly.

01:30:10.520 --> 01:30:16.040
[Guest]: And to me, I mean, those are kind of my, in my intellectual journey, those were kind of,

01:30:16.040 --> 01:30:19.920
[Guest]: you know, landmarks that how could I ask?

01:30:19.920 --> 01:30:21.320
[Guest]: How could I think?

01:30:21.320 --> 01:30:24.200
[Guest]: And I think this is where the demography, the population issue, and this issue also

01:30:24.200 --> 01:30:25.200
[Guest]: fits in.

01:30:25.200 --> 01:30:30.640
[Guest]: That, that it's not in the numbers, in terms of population.

01:30:30.640 --> 01:30:36.320
[Guest]: And it's not in the scarcity in terms of tigers or chickens or crocodiles or whatever.

01:30:36.320 --> 01:30:43.000
[Guest]: That these are all constructs and outcomes of certain way of looking at things.

01:30:43.000 --> 01:30:49.840
[Guest]: And because of certain ways of looking at things, we construct our policies to fit that,

01:30:49.840 --> 01:30:53.340
[Guest]: which may not be the whole story.

01:30:53.340 --> 01:30:56.800
[Guest]: And at the back of my mind, and this is where, this is where kind of, you know, the other

01:30:56.800 --> 01:31:04.760
[Guest]: dimension plays in and where both Rand and Gandhi is quite important, which is what happens

01:31:04.760 --> 01:31:05.760
[Guest]: when you impose?

01:31:05.760 --> 01:31:10.200
[Guest]: You know, we think we impose because we know.

01:31:10.200 --> 01:31:14.800
[Guest]: What happens if we, if we are wrong, and we have imposed?

01:31:14.800 --> 01:31:19.880
[Guest]: Emergency was a very good experience and a tragic one of what happened when somebody

01:31:19.880 --> 01:31:23.960
[Guest]: believed in something and imposed it on others, and what was the cost?

01:31:23.960 --> 01:31:29.480
[Guest]: You know, it was a human experience and a tragedy of enormous proportion, you know,

01:31:29.480 --> 01:31:33.840
[Guest]: something comparable to, to, to what happened in some of the communist countries because

01:31:33.840 --> 01:31:37.320
[Guest]: of the whims and fancies of their leaders.

01:31:37.320 --> 01:31:39.280
[Guest]: That is where the ethics comes in.

01:31:39.280 --> 01:31:46.780
[Guest]: That what do I really, even if I know, do I have the right to impose?

01:31:46.780 --> 01:31:48.520
[Amit Varma]: What happens if I'm wrong?

01:31:48.520 --> 01:31:52.080
[Guest]: And the impositions aren't just during the emergency, but all of our history, essentially.

01:31:52.080 --> 01:31:53.080
[Guest]: The mindset continues.

01:31:53.080 --> 01:32:00.320
[Guest]: It is this mindset that has impacted our policy on environment, on tigers or on everything.

01:32:00.320 --> 01:32:04.880
[Guest]: The mindset is that, you know, that is where that we are looking at policy in a frame that

01:32:04.880 --> 01:32:10.520
[Guest]: we have internalized without reflecting what impact or what's the relevance for it for

01:32:10.520 --> 01:32:11.520
[Guest]: the public.

01:32:11.520 --> 01:32:14.760
[Guest]: Like you said about, about the Northeast, what the people wanted and what the, what

01:32:14.760 --> 01:32:18.120
[Guest]: the funding was, the state funding was aimed at doing.

01:32:18.120 --> 01:32:25.800
[Guest]: So that gap, it's not just a gap, it's the mindset that makes us do that, which is where,

01:32:25.800 --> 01:32:31.920
[Guest]: which is where carrying people along as Gandhi showed is so critical because we wouldn't

01:32:31.920 --> 01:32:37.520
[Guest]: be able to carry people along if we persisted in, in, on that track for long.

01:32:37.520 --> 01:32:42.080
[Guest]: I mean, that might be an initial, and we can see that we have so many campaigns on so many

01:32:42.080 --> 01:32:46.640
[Guest]: social political issues, but what kind of a shelf life do they have?

01:32:46.640 --> 01:32:50.960
[Guest]: You know, we need another campaign as if to overcome the current campaign.

01:32:50.960 --> 01:32:54.800
[Guest]: Because the current campaign shelf life is over, so we need another drama to take it

01:32:54.800 --> 01:32:59.640
[Guest]: forward to the, you know, take it, take the next, next campaign in order to keep the people

01:32:59.640 --> 01:33:02.480
[Guest]: addicted to something.

01:33:02.480 --> 01:33:10.860
[Guest]: So while we can keep doing it, but are we achieving anything meaningful or are we achieving

01:33:10.860 --> 01:33:16.220
[Guest]: the kind of change that I'm sure most of us would agree on?

01:33:16.220 --> 01:33:22.920
[Guest]: And I think, I think, yeah, so that ethics part, and then the natural this thing was,

01:33:22.920 --> 01:33:29.800
[Guest]: which I think we've discussed earlier too, which is many of us may agree on the ends.

01:33:29.800 --> 01:33:32.680
[Guest]: We need to look at the means.

01:33:32.680 --> 01:33:39.840
[Guest]: We need to look at the means and we cannot achieve our ends unless the means relate to

01:33:39.840 --> 01:33:41.840
[Guest]: the, to the ends.

01:33:41.840 --> 01:33:47.680
[Guest]: And this is where even a non-believer, non-practitioner, non-temple grower, a beef-eating Hindu can

01:33:47.680 --> 01:33:55.040
[Guest]: claim to be a Hindu, which I do, I have no reason yet to disown my legacy or my, yeah,

01:33:55.040 --> 01:33:59.080
[Guest]: my legacy, my presence in the Hindu fold.

01:33:59.080 --> 01:34:05.320
[Guest]: But I can completely relate, for instance, to the essence of Gita, you know, without

01:34:05.320 --> 01:34:06.880
[Guest]: having any divinity in it.

01:34:06.880 --> 01:34:07.880
[Amit Varma]: In fact…

01:34:07.880 --> 01:34:10.920
[Amit Varma]: The central message of the Gita is that the end justifies the means.

01:34:10.920 --> 01:34:12.200
[Guest]: It's exactly the opposite.

01:34:12.200 --> 01:34:14.120
[Guest]: The whole, yeah, it's exactly the opposite.

01:34:14.120 --> 01:34:19.680
[Guest]: It's the whole quest for finding the means that the end is whatever.

01:34:19.680 --> 01:34:22.120
[Amit Varma]: We agree that we have to win the war or whatever.

01:34:22.120 --> 01:34:23.760
[Amit Varma]: And the means is kill all your cousins.

01:34:23.760 --> 01:34:24.760
[Guest]: No.

01:34:24.760 --> 01:34:31.120
[Guest]: Why and how you do it, the whole discourse is that, that a God, those who believe in

01:34:31.120 --> 01:34:38.320
[Guest]: divinity of Krishna, couldn't dictate or order or press a button.

01:34:38.320 --> 01:34:43.880
[Guest]: But he had to engage in such a dialogue at such a critical point in general to just convince

01:34:43.880 --> 01:34:47.640
[Guest]: someone that this is why and this is how you should engage.

01:34:47.640 --> 01:34:48.640
[Guest]: To me, it is this process.

01:34:48.640 --> 01:34:49.640
[Guest]: That's the means.

01:34:49.640 --> 01:34:51.200
[Guest]: Not the specifics or the details.

01:34:51.200 --> 01:34:52.200
[Guest]: That's irrelevant.

01:34:52.200 --> 01:34:59.880
[Guest]: It's this process of searching, of questioning continuously till you are convinced.

01:34:59.880 --> 01:35:04.480
[Guest]: Now, the conclusion at a particular point in time may turn out to be wrong.

01:35:04.480 --> 01:35:05.920
[Guest]: Later on, you have to change.

01:35:05.920 --> 01:35:06.920
[Guest]: But that's life always.

01:35:06.920 --> 01:35:11.480
[Guest]: So, my reading of Gita is completely different and I think my reading of Gita is actually

01:35:11.480 --> 01:35:17.520
[Guest]: quite consonant with quite a few people who have actually interpreted Gita from the original

01:35:17.520 --> 01:35:19.960
[Guest]: because I am reading in Bengali or in English.

01:35:19.960 --> 01:35:30.480
[Guest]: But people who read it in Sanskrit, I mean, I find this essence of action detached from

01:35:30.480 --> 01:35:39.640
[Guest]: the outcome is possible only when you have the capacity in your mind that you have got

01:35:39.640 --> 01:35:41.320
[Guest]: the means right.

01:35:41.320 --> 01:35:42.320
[Guest]: And then it's free for all.

01:35:42.320 --> 01:35:43.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:35:43.320 --> 01:35:44.320
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I'm not an expert on the Gita.

01:35:44.320 --> 01:35:45.320
[Guest]: Neither am I.

01:35:45.320 --> 01:35:49.760
[Amit Varma]: And there are things I admire greatly about the book, for example, you know, I think Lord

01:35:49.760 --> 01:35:53.120
[Amit Varma]: Krishna would have made a great poker player in just his lesson of don't worry about the

01:35:53.120 --> 01:35:57.840
[Amit Varma]: fruits of your action, just do the right thing, which is very, you know, non-results oriented,

01:35:57.840 --> 01:36:01.160
[Amit Varma]: process oriented, lots to learn there for modern sportsmen also.

01:36:01.160 --> 01:36:06.040
[Amit Varma]: But then I look at, you know, what the Pandavas did, like our friend Mohit was pointing out

01:36:06.040 --> 01:36:10.480
[Amit Varma]: last night at dinner that they killed almost all their main enemies by deception.

01:36:10.480 --> 01:36:13.600
[Amit Varma]: I just feel that there's an issue there with the means, but that's a larger discussion

01:36:13.600 --> 01:36:14.760
[Amit Varma]: and it's a great book on its own.

01:36:14.760 --> 01:36:16.000
[Amit Varma]: I won't get into that.

01:36:16.000 --> 01:36:19.720
[Amit Varma]: I do want to talk about means and ends and Gandhi after the break.

01:36:19.720 --> 01:36:23.880
[Amit Varma]: But before the break, one more piece of context setting and then a joke that you might like

01:36:23.880 --> 01:36:25.200
[Amit Varma]: and you must have heard.

01:36:25.200 --> 01:36:28.920
[Amit Varma]: So the context setting is that I also want to double click on what you said earlier for

01:36:28.920 --> 01:36:32.840
[Amit Varma]: the reader's benefit, that in the Western world, the consumption is high, the wealth

01:36:32.840 --> 01:36:35.280
[Amit Varma]: is high and the air is clean.

01:36:35.280 --> 01:36:38.880
[Amit Varma]: And this is like something that I remember is counterintuitive.

01:36:38.880 --> 01:36:42.880
[Amit Varma]: And I first read about it in Beyond Lombok's book, The Skeptical Environmentalist when

01:36:42.880 --> 01:36:45.200
[Amit Varma]: it came out 16 or 17 years ago.

01:36:45.200 --> 01:36:49.360
[Amit Varma]: Great book then, kind of outdated now, but do follow Beyond Lombok's recent writings

01:36:49.360 --> 01:36:50.360
[Amit Varma]: if you can.

01:36:50.360 --> 01:36:55.160
[Amit Varma]: The revelation there was that London at the end of the 19th century was possibly as polluted

01:36:55.160 --> 01:36:57.720
[Amit Varma]: as Bombay is today or even Delhi is today.

01:36:57.720 --> 01:37:00.760
[Amit Varma]: All these great Western cities were incredibly populated.

01:37:00.760 --> 01:37:05.560
[Amit Varma]: But there was like a sort of a bell curve of pollution that once you reached a certain

01:37:05.560 --> 01:37:11.640
[Amit Varma]: level of economic growth and a certain level of wealth, these cities started becoming cleaner.

01:37:11.640 --> 01:37:14.440
[Amit Varma]: The Kuznets curve in a sense, you could also apply that.

01:37:14.440 --> 01:37:19.400
[Amit Varma]: And they started getting much, much cleaner because technology became better, people started

01:37:19.400 --> 01:37:25.120
[Amit Varma]: applying ingenuity, citizens became more empowered and demanded cleaner air, combination of reasons

01:37:25.120 --> 01:37:27.840
[Amit Varma]: and the wealth that enabled it.

01:37:27.840 --> 01:37:29.120
[Amit Varma]: And the wealth that enabled it.

01:37:29.120 --> 01:37:35.080
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, a city like London today consumes much more than it used to, has many more people

01:37:35.080 --> 01:37:38.080
[Amit Varma]: than it used to, and is much, much cleaner than it used to.

01:37:38.080 --> 01:37:44.000
[Guest]: And the last I heard was Thames, the water in the Thames is potable.

01:37:44.000 --> 01:37:45.000
[Guest]: Wow.

01:37:45.000 --> 01:37:46.000
[Guest]: Unbelievable.

01:37:46.000 --> 01:37:53.400
[Guest]: And that it happened, you know, 150 years Londoners and English literature has been

01:37:53.400 --> 01:37:59.080
[Guest]: lamenting, you know, the fog, the famous Jack the Ripper and the London fog at the turn

01:37:59.080 --> 01:38:01.360
[Guest]: of the last century.

01:38:01.360 --> 01:38:11.880
[Guest]: But post war, in about less than 20 years, things had changed so dramatically, you know,

01:38:11.880 --> 01:38:17.600
[Guest]: and post colonization because London was no longer the imperial capital during that phase,

01:38:17.600 --> 01:38:24.760
[Guest]: it lost most of its, almost all of its colonies, yet the city, and it's not just about London.

01:38:24.760 --> 01:38:25.760
[Amit Varma]: So many other cities.

01:38:25.760 --> 01:38:26.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:38:26.760 --> 01:38:27.760
[Guest]: I mean, not just cities.

01:38:27.760 --> 01:38:34.480
[Guest]: England today has more trees standing and more wooded areas than a century or more ago.

01:38:34.480 --> 01:38:39.840
[Guest]: United States today has more trees standing and more wooded areas than a century ago.

01:38:39.840 --> 01:38:40.840
[Guest]: How has it happened?

01:38:40.840 --> 01:38:48.160
[Guest]: You know, so we need to, so to me, it is this relationship between the lived experience,

01:38:48.160 --> 01:38:53.320
[Guest]: provided we are willing to open our eyes to see what has happened and then trying to figure

01:38:53.320 --> 01:38:56.560
[Guest]: out how and why it has happened.

01:38:56.560 --> 01:39:00.880
[Guest]: So that we can see what are the lessons that can be drawn, because we don't have to, you

01:39:00.880 --> 01:39:06.680
[Guest]: know, the Kuznets curve, actually the beauty of the Kuznets curve is because societies

01:39:06.680 --> 01:39:12.880
[Guest]: that are developing later, like India is and many others, can leapfrog.

01:39:12.880 --> 01:39:18.000
[Guest]: So the peak of pollution, which the Western societies industrialized, the societies that

01:39:18.000 --> 01:39:25.320
[Guest]: were industrializing at first, that level should not be, need not be reached by anyone

01:39:25.320 --> 01:39:26.320
[Guest]: who's following.

01:39:26.320 --> 01:39:32.560
[Guest]: So we should make that turn much quicker, provided we get the lessons and the perspectives

01:39:32.560 --> 01:39:33.560
[Amit Varma]: right.

01:39:33.560 --> 01:39:34.560
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

01:39:34.560 --> 01:39:38.040
[Amit Varma]: And then Steven Pinker has also written very eloquently about, you know, how we think the

01:39:38.040 --> 01:39:41.840
[Amit Varma]: world is getting worse, but actually it is just such a much better place.

01:39:41.840 --> 01:39:44.920
[Amit Varma]: And now the joke I promised you before we go to the break, and this has something to

01:39:44.920 --> 01:39:48.560
[Amit Varma]: do with what you mentioned about how when you were a kid, you wouldn't eat chickens

01:39:48.560 --> 01:39:52.880
[Amit Varma]: and you'd sometimes, you'd eat a lot of mutton and sometimes you'd eat ducks.

01:39:52.880 --> 01:39:56.040
[Amit Varma]: Now ducks, as you know, the Hindi word for ducks is batak, right?

01:39:56.040 --> 01:40:00.960
[Amit Varma]: So there is this famous story about how Gyani Zayal Singh, when he was president of India,

01:40:00.960 --> 01:40:06.280
[Amit Varma]: he was in England and the Queen of England took him on a walk around the, you know, Buckingham

01:40:06.280 --> 01:40:08.480
[Amit Varma]: Palace or wherever the Royal Gardens are.

01:40:08.480 --> 01:40:11.440
[Amit Varma]: And there was a pond there and there were some beautiful ducks there.

01:40:11.440 --> 01:40:15.160
[Amit Varma]: And Gyani Zayal Singh turned to the Queen and said, Madam, you have lovely buttocks.

01:40:15.160 --> 01:40:19.880
[Guest]: Of course, for a Bengali, that's not exactly the word we use for ducks.

01:40:19.880 --> 01:40:20.880
[Amit Varma]: What's the word you use?

01:40:20.880 --> 01:40:21.880
[Amit Varma]: Harsh.

01:40:21.880 --> 01:40:22.880
[Amit Varma]: Harsh.

01:40:22.880 --> 01:40:23.880
[Guest]: But buttocks, I'm right, right?

01:40:23.880 --> 01:40:26.880
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, in Hindi, that's what you'd say.

01:40:26.880 --> 01:40:27.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah.

01:40:27.880 --> 01:40:28.880
[Guest]: Delightful.

01:40:28.880 --> 01:40:33.440
[Amit Varma]: But of course, I had the fish option too, being a Bengali, fish is our second special.

01:40:33.440 --> 01:40:34.440
[Amit Varma]: March.

01:40:34.440 --> 01:40:35.440
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:40:35.440 --> 01:40:36.440
[Amit Varma]: Great.

